INSERT INTO `word` VALUES ('dismay','00b047d3799897cfa0c04f164c79ee76',NULL,'uncount noun','Dismay is a strong feeling of fear, worry, or sadness that is caused by something unpleasant and unexpected.','Local politicians have reacted with dismay and indignation.',3,'/dɪsmeɪ/'),('court','020696dcd5f418ad62b60c446dca2bb3',NULL,'transitive verb','If you court something such as publicity or popularity, you try to attract it.','Having spent a lifetime avidly courting publicity, Paul has suddenly become secretive.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('mania','02736f2a266c6cadea5f8f1a6ba8a669',NULL,'uncount noun','Mania is a mental illness which causes the sufferer to become very worried or concerned about something.','...the treatment of mania.',3,'/meɪniə/'),('downcast','02d101b4f39b1610aef32f950b4a1a37',NULL,'adjective','If your eyes are downcast, you are looking toward the ground, usually because you are feeling sad or embarrassed.','She was silent, her eyes downcast.',2,'/daʊnkæst/'),('try','02fce574fd8431cf6f9e76bd6bdb3820',NULL,'transitive verb','To try and do something means to try to do it.','I must try and see him.',5,'/traɪ/'),('try','03f5263b6932d3b25c6301cc41a0e3dc',NULL,'transitive verb','When a person is tried, he or she has to appear in a law court and is found innocent or guilty after the judge and jury have heard the evidence. When a legal case is tried, it is considered in a court of law.','He suggested that those responsible should be tried for crimes against humanity.\nWhether he is innocent or guilty is a decision that will be made when the case is tried in court.',5,'/traɪ/'),('hesitate','041f51d9123292ce4c779c73debdf1b7',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you hesitate, you do not speak or act for a short time, usually because you are uncertain, embarrassed, or worried about what you are going to say or do.','The telephone rang. Catherine hesitated, debating whether to answer it.\nAsked if he would go back, Mr. Searle said after some hesitation, \"I\'ll have to think about that.\"',3,'/hɛzɪteɪt/'),('upset','04505e8278f6c997bce66eec30761763',NULL,'transitive verb','If something upsets you, it makes you feel worried or unhappy.','The whole incident had upset me and my fiancée terribly.\nShe warned me not to say anything to upset him.\nChildhood sickness can be upsetting for children and parents alike.',4,'/ʌpsɛt/ /ʌpsɛt/'),('strain','04533947f3cffe541705b165371eb384',NULL,'countable noun','A strain of a germ, plant, or other organism is a particular type of it.','Every year new strains of influenza develop.',4,'/streɪn/'),('relieve','0459013e04a23476439e992ad2718d28',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone is relieved of their duties or is relieved of their post, they are told that they are no longer required to continue in their job.','The officer involved was relieved of his duties because he had violated strict guidelines.',0,'/rɪliv/'),('miserable','054888812501fde7ed95b330a6024433',NULL,'adjective','If you describe the weather as miserable, you mean that it makes you feel depressed, because it is raining or dull.','On a gray, wet, miserable day our teams congregated in Port Townsend.',3,'/mɪzərəbəl/'),('profane','05c80b5bcbc4d3bf0d3dd065cb3b8314',NULL,'adjective','Something that is profane is concerned with everyday life rather than religion and spiritual things.','Cardinal Daly has said that churches should not be used for profane or secular purposes.',3,'/prəfeɪn/'),('long','05d2e4d9fbaa49017cd5149b9c02925d',NULL,'adverb','Long is used in expressions such as all year long, the whole day long, and your whole life long to say and emphasize that something happens for the whole of a particular period of time.','We played that CD all night long.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('uncanny','060a8a22571b9fb796b19dcb93ecea5b',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something as uncanny, you mean that it is strange and difficult to explain.','The hero, Danny, bears an uncanny resemblance to Kirk Douglas.\nThey have uncannily similar voices.',3,'/ʌnkæni/'),('striking','06937967f34b770ff18f1f66bb84d2f3',NULL,'adjective','Something that is striking is very noticeable or unusual.','The most striking feature of those statistics is the high proportion of suicides.\nHe bears a striking resemblance to Lenin.\nIn one respect, however, the men really were strikingly similar.\n...a strikingly handsome man.',4,'/straɪkɪŋ/'),('mean','077d8692784d471a25d8a730e0933df8',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that you mean what you are saying, you are telling someone that you are serious about it and are not joking, exaggerating, or just being polite.','He says you\'re fired if you\'re not back at work on Friday. And I think he meant it.',5,'/min/'),('readily','07a20624061a9d9a71dd4b4a36cd14a5',NULL,'adverb','You also use readily to say that something can be done or obtained quickly and easily. For example, if you say that something can be readily understood, you mean that people can understand it quickly and easily.','The components are readily available in hardware stores.',4,'/rɛdɪli/'),('doubt','07db1c416b2910b0b455392a0c0389f4',NULL,'transitive verb','If you doubt something, you believe that it might not be true or genuine.','No one doubted his ability.',4,'/daʊt/'),('ardent','07f89669f69bee2836b84d5d68cc54c4',NULL,'adjective','Ardent is used to describe someone who has extremely strong feelings about something or someone.','He\'s been one of the most ardent supporters of the administration\'s policy.',3,'/ɑrdənt/'),('uproar','084f140e6e425e6b3775241a521ae1f3',NULL,'uncount noun','You can also use uproar to refer to a lot of public criticism and debate about something that has made people angry.','The town is in an uproar over the dispute.',3,'/ʌprɔr/'),('curious','0938509e6f1b0dde87f77798b3fabb4d',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something as curious, you mean that it is unusual or difficult to understand.','The pageant promises to be a curious mixture of the ancient and modern.\nHarry was curiously silent through all this.',4,'/kyʊəriəs/'),('readily','09b01afa52e31d2b7f9bf6052720eefb',NULL,'adverb','If you do something readily, you do it in a way which shows that you are very willing to do it.','I asked her if she would allow me to interview her, and she readily agreed.',4,'/rɛdɪli/'),('court','09c5a5d81a24a854f2ea08a9061e1dfc',NULL,'countable noun','A court is an area in which you play a game such as tennis, basketball, badminton, or squash.','The hotel has several tennis and squash courts.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('begrudge','0a8b9fa01724e61644fd450396c1855b',NULL,'transitive verb','If you do not begrudge someone something, you do not feel angry, upset, or jealous that they have it.','I certainly don\'t begrudge him the Nobel Prize.',2,'/bɪgrʌdʒ/'),('zealous','0b5522e5a8fcc7c4ea897f76525114fd',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is zealous spends a lot of time or energy in supporting something that they believe in very strongly, especially a political or religious ideal.','She was a zealous worker for charity.',3,'/zɛləs/'),('beat','0cead84bab12f8bab2c4e6bc46797d2f',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that one thing beats another, you mean that it is better than it.','Being boss of a software firm beats selling insurance.',4,'/bit/'),('hail','0cfab93d892c837221135c27a0e9b10e',NULL,'uncount noun','Hail consists of small balls of ice that fall like rain from the sky.','...a sharp short-lived storm with heavy hail.',3,'/heɪl/'),('hunger','0d007c7fc6cf9671b50e7ca8fa6129cb',NULL,'uncount noun','Hunger is a severe lack of food which causes suffering or death.','Three hundred people in this town are dying of hunger every day.',4,'/hʌŋgər/'),('abashed','0d5bdff0b6cce6d10fd478863af5989e',NULL,'adjective','If you are abashed, you feel embarrassed and ashamed.','He looked abashed and uncomfortable.',0,'/əbæʃt/'),('brisk','0d98a8f0328c900896c056d8705d2743',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is brisk behaves in a busy, confident way which shows that they want to get things done quickly.','The Chief summoned me downstairs. He was brisk and businesslike.\n\"Anyhow,\" she added briskly, \"it\'s none of my business.\"',3,'/brɪsk/'),('fussy','0e3dd07049bba6da491eb7cd789efe85',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is fussy is very concerned with unimportant details and is difficult to please.','She is not fussy about her food.',2,'/fʌsi/'),('flat','0f0e92d4c12321ed80b3e0ee180ad496',NULL,'adjective','Flat land is level, with no high hills or other raised parts.','To the north lie the flat and fertile farmlands of Nebraska.',3,'/flæt/'),('suspect','0fc9ee4ded439af09bee6cdd60c0c139',NULL,'countable noun','A suspect is a person who the police or authorities think may be guilty of a crime.','Police have arrested a suspect in a series of killings and sexual assaults in the city.',4,'/səspɛkt/ /sʌspɛkt/'),('depress','101a07420e3a7f0cd1d17d6374425857',NULL,'transitive verb','If something depresses prices, wages, or figures, it causes them to become less.','The stronger U.S. dollar depressed sales.',2,'/dɪprɛs/'),('disgust','1062caaf9e6a560bd0ea01c60690955c',NULL,'transitive verb','To disgust someone means to make them feel a strong sense of dislike and disapproval.','He disgusted many with his boorish behavior.',3,'/dɪsgʌst/'),('doubt','1094d36b1a0a4f0f7405196ea4f86bb8',NULL,'phrase','You say that something is beyond doubt or beyond reasonable doubt when you are certain that it is true and it cannot be contradicted or disproved.','A referendum showed beyond doubt that voters wanted independence.',4,'/daʊt/'),('begrudge','10bc4018ceb916615908e21a8e006401',NULL,'transitive verb','If you do not begrudge something such as time or money, you do not mind giving it up.','I do not begrudge the money I have lost.',2,'/bɪgrʌdʒ/'),('sick','1151e3b8544368e9f07f2060cf8cfd23',NULL,'phrase','If you say that you are worried sick, you are emphasizing that you are extremely worried.','He was worried sick about what our mothers would say.',4,'/sɪk/'),('abhorrent','1215d155595ca61e950cb04162b69ad0',NULL,'adjective','If something is abhorrent to you, you hate it very much or consider it completely unacceptable.','Racial discrimination is abhorrent to my council and our staff.',2,'/æbhɔrənt/'),('please','121e90b0f1f07e638ffdabe720bf48b5',NULL,'convention','You can say please to indicate that you want someone to stop doing something or stop speaking. You would say this if, for example, what they are doing or saying makes you angry or upset.','Please, Mary, this is all so unnecessary.',3,'/pliz/'),('touch','13037c6cfba3227030cca2b899c2f492',NULL,'transitive verb','To touch something means to strike it, usually quite gently.','He scored the first time he touched the ball.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('misery','13a6d021ccc8cae7240013c547c999ff',NULL,'variable noun','Misery is great unhappiness.','All that money brought nothing but sadness and misery and tragedy.',3,'/mɪzəri/'),('scare','13ac955272f0cf6816a4dc55a77706f1',NULL,'singular noun','If a sudden unpleasant experience gives you a scare, it frightens you.','Don\'t you realize what a scare you\'ve given us all?',3,'/skɛər/'),('miserable','142f26da99eb90d09c1648c996e0670b',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone as miserable, you mean that you do not like them because they are bad-tempered or unfriendly.','He always was a miserable man. He never spoke to me nor anybody else, not even to pass the time of day.',3,'/mɪzərəbəl/'),('enrapture','1515b158b4bcda541a939b1ab03c3406',NULL,'transitive verb','If something or someone enraptures you, you think they are wonderful or fascinating.','The place at once enraptured me.\nThe 20,000-strong audience listened, enraptured.\n...an enraptured audience.',1,'/ɪnræptʃər/'),('hospitable','15b0b37d20a60b3d09255672c2823768',NULL,'adjective','A hospitable climate or environment is one that encourages the existence or development of particular people or things.','Even in summer this place did not look exactly hospitable: in winter, conditions must have been exceedingly harsh.',3,'/hɒspɪtəbəl/'),('concern','15c2b5f7686928d0ff236720ede8d6b5',NULL,'singular noun','If a situation or problem is your concern, it is something that you have a duty or responsibility to be involved with.','The technical aspects were the concern of the Army.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('long','16240f796a84473b4602e436262d5073',NULL,'adverb','Long means a great amount of time or for a great amount of time.','Repairs to the cable did not take too long.\nHave you known her parents long?\nI learned long ago to avoid these invitations.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('frenzy','1630e5d9aa775e92349949bd473112a1',NULL,'variable noun','Frenzy or a frenzy is great excitement or wild behavior that often results from losing control of your feelings.','\"Get out!\" she ordered in a frenzy.',3,'/frɛnzi/'),('affection','16e12abb2192186664c0451851b96612',NULL,'uncount noun','If you regard someone or something with affection, you like them and are fond of them.','She thought of him with affection.',4,'/əfɛkʃən/'),('doubt','17092adb00088e5d266dafb33d72394e',NULL,'transitive verb','If you doubt whether something is true or possible, you believe that it is probably not true or possible.','Others doubted whether that would happen.\nHe doubted if he would learn anything new from Marie.',4,'/daʊt/'),('doubt','175d2c0b2fdb5c604636c6ff1c2f7230',NULL,'phrase','If you say that something is in doubt or open to doubt, you consider it to be uncertain or unreliable.','The outcome was still in doubt.',4,'/daʊt/'),('menace','183bbe375d115bd33abd110926a119f3',NULL,'countable noun','If you say that someone or something is a menace to other people or things, you mean that person or thing is likely to cause serious harm.','In my view, you are a menace to the public.',3,'/mɛnɪs/'),('dismal','1868626beba256c1344a63980c16b8eb',NULL,'adjective','Something that is dismal is bad in a sad or depressing way.','...Israel\'s dismal record in the Olympics.',3,'/dɪzməl/'),('faint','18eea61a6a87cbd989d81b310717a842',NULL,'adjective','Faint is also a noun.','She slumped to the ground in a faint.',3,'/feɪnt/'),('fanatic','1943a5c76df5998f5334914ecf2c1cf2',NULL,'adjective','Fanatic means the same as   fanatical.','',2,'/fənætɪk/'),('affection','19d5e414073b510a0cbfab16c55bceeb',NULL,'plural noun','Your affections are your feelings of love or fondness for someone.','Caroline is the object of his affections.',4,'/əfɛkʃən/'),('suspense','19ff6fa7a9ba2df537a8d08077e31f5a',NULL,'uncount noun','Suspense is a state of excitement or anxiety about something that is going to happen very soon, for example about some news that you are waiting to hear.','The suspense over the two remaining hostages ended last night when the police discovered the bullet ridden bodies.',3,'/səspɛns/'),('aspire','1a0081636496b3de0c7489ffa324b38e',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you aspire to something such as an important job, you have a strong desire to achieve it.','...people who aspire to public office.\nRice aspired to go to college.',3,'/əspaɪər/'),('impassive','1a2b741d751116eac9b2584ab60e273c',NULL,'adjective','If someone is impassive or their face is impassive, they are not showing any emotion.','He searched Hill\'s impassive face for some indication that he understood.\nThe lawyer looked impassively at him and said nothing.',2,'/ɪmpæsɪv/'),('pleasure','1a447a3430f7a4fa03a81a32eb98edbb',NULL,'countable noun','A pleasure is an activity, experience, or aspect of something that you find very enjoyable or satisfying.','Watching TV is our only pleasure.\n...the pleasure of seeing a smiling face.',4,'/plɛʒər/'),('strike','1a5e5b14fb97be544324991983791bfc',NULL,'reciprocal verb','If you strike a deal or a bargain with someone, you come to an agreement with them.','They struck a deal with their paper supplier, getting two years of newsprint on credit.\nThe two struck a deal in which Rendell took half of what a manager would.',4,'/straɪk/'),('concern','1a6bd5eacf44914967ae36f9cbdcd3e5',NULL,'countable noun','A concern is a fact or situation that worries you.','His concern was that people would know that he was responsible.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('positive','1ac32ae41046327dd9bfbed2c4605d97',NULL,'adjective','Positive evidence gives definite proof of the truth or identity of something.','There was no positive evidence that any birth defects had arisen as a result of Vitamin A intake.\nHe has positively identified the body as that of his wife.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('suspicion','1bbad0e8baef2c3ba43071dee67ec866',NULL,'countable noun','A suspicion is a feeling that something is probably true or is likely to happen.','I have a sneaking suspicion that they are going to succeed.',4,'/səspɪʃən/'),('hilarious','1c05ebaff038cfb6c5820e991db52a71',NULL,'adjective','If something is hilarious, it is extremely funny and makes you laugh a lot.','We thought it was hilarious when we first heard about it.\nShe found it hilariously funny.',3,'/hɪlɛəriəs/'),('strain','1ce1deea5f7dfce7d866fb248c6dc64b',NULL,'transitive verb','If you strain to do something, you make a great effort to do it when it is difficult to do.','I had to strain to hear.',4,'/streɪn/'),('long','1db90e9bddbd453cda9b928970d0e26d',NULL,'adjective','You use long to talk or ask about the distance something measures from one end to the other.','An eight-week-old embryo is only an inch long.\nHow long is the tunnel?',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('impassioned','1ee0253d247c90e6e7e221a005491245',NULL,'adjective','An impassioned speech or piece of writing is one in which someone expresses their strong feelings about an issue in a forceful way.','He made an impassioned appeal for peace.',3,'/ɪmpæʃənd/'),('court','1f66e362a965fd691f51e1e1a059f387',NULL,'countable noun','A court is a place where legal matters are decided by a judge and jury or by a magistrate.','At this rate, we could find ourselves in the divorce courts!\n...a county court judge.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('ecstasy','1fb7f8aa4c2a34d74738b953e3ca3292',NULL,'variable noun','Ecstasy is a feeling of very great happiness.','...a state of almost religious ecstasy.',3,'/ɛkstəsi/'),('joyous','1fe851663ffe994ff8cf12ab7c28b6d3',NULL,'adjective','Joyous means extremely happy.','She had made their childhood so joyous and carefree.\nSarah accepted joyously.',3,'/dʒɔɪəs/'),('beat','20110eafb97bbfabd9f0804551520a04',NULL,'transitive verb','If you beat something that you are fighting against, for example, an organization, a problem, or a disease, you defeat it.','It became clear that the Union was not going to beat the government.',4,'/bit/'),('horror','20bd0bedb88339dff1158bbd5833def8',NULL,'singular noun','If you have a horror of something, you are afraid of it or dislike it very much.','...his horror of death.',4,'/hɔrər/'),('positive','212d2944c577d9ed9b40a25c0fe2f7b7',NULL,'adjective','If you are positive about something, you are completely sure about it.','\"Judith\'s never late. You sure she said eight?\"—\"Positive.\"',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('touch','21421458dc20088e1cd93791abbfbd4c',NULL,'transitive verb','If something touches you, it affects you in some way for a short time.','...a guilt that in some sense touches everyone.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('harass','216c4cd3607da3485637eb1a32fc0967',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone harasses you, they trouble or annoy you, for example by attacking you repeatedly or by causing you as many problems as they can.','A woman reporter complained one of them sexually harassed her in the locker room.',2,'/həræs/'),('vigorous','21af461a1f35d22022746fd546b9672f',NULL,'adjective','A vigorous person does things with great energy and enthusiasm. A vigorous campaign or activity is done with great energy and enthusiasm.','Theodore Roosevelt was a strong and vigorous politician.\nThe police vigorously denied that excessive force had been used.',3,'/vɪgərəs/'),('mean','21dab9cde57dd8414f0b2adaf82c5f8a',NULL,'phrase','If you know what it means to do something, you know everything that is involved in a particular activity or experience, especially the effect that it has on you.','I know what it means to lose a child under such tragic circumstances.',5,'/min/'),('cheerless','21fc83b4c3140fc19bf445bf666a48a9',NULL,'adjective','Cheerless places or weather are dull and depressing.','The kitchen was dank and cheerless.\n...a bleak, cheerless day.',2,'/tʃɪərlɪs/'),('poise','225fd83f0bc105bbded8813ceb9d00d4',NULL,'uncount noun','If someone has poise, they are calm, dignified, and self-controlled.','What amazed him even more than her appearance was her poise.',2,'/pɔɪz/'),('gratify','22da806a437bb0bb5ffd5e7e6cd9f6e0',NULL,'transitive verb','If you gratify your own or another person\'s desire, you do what is necessary to please yourself or them.','We gratified our friend\'s curiosity.\n...sexual gratification.',2,'/grætɪfaɪ/'),('flat','22e2f0fff296e2eaf3cb7529df5aaeff',NULL,'adjective','A drink that is flat has lost its fizz.','Could this really stop the champagne from going flat?',3,'/flæt/'),('strike','235e6ca43b6f6f2eb7129d5f7817c8c2',NULL,'transitive verb','If you are struck by something, you think it is very impressive, noticeable, or interesting.','She was struck by his simple, spellbinding eloquence.',4,'/straɪk/'),('long','23631b1df34a630d05b1cf4f2570935d',NULL,'adjective','A long distance is a great distance. A long journey or route covers a great distance.','These people were a long way from home.\nThe long journey tired him.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('halt','238201378473854058373284081a2701',NULL,'phrase','If someone calls a halt to something such as an activity, they decide not to continue with it or to end it immediately.','The Russian government had called a halt to the construction of a new project in the Rostov region.',3,'/hɔlt/'),('sinister','23b0f9ad363de7ea643940a0faf4b3de',NULL,'adjective','Something that is sinister seems evil or harmful.','There was something sinister about him that she found disturbing.',3,'/sɪnɪstər/'),('impatient','23d05dc419f353429427acf4c0772294',NULL,'adjective','If you are impatient, you are annoyed because you have to wait too long for something.','Investors are growing impatient with promises of improved earnings.\nPeople have been waiting impatiently for a chance to improve the situation.\nThere is considerable impatience with the slow pace of political change.',3,'/ɪmpeɪʃənt/'),('faint','2406e508adf8019a826b784a0d87cdb5',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is faint feels weak and unsteady as if they are about to lose consciousness.','Other signs of angina are nausea, sweating, feeling faint and shortness of breath.',3,'/feɪnt/'),('strike','24716e3013d981191cd0c4286d301665',NULL,'intransitive verb','To strike means to attack someone or something quickly and violently.','He was the only cabinet member out of the country when the terrorists struck.',4,'/straɪk/'),('crazy','24d22aacfdb34610dbd2d5517b44e585',NULL,'adjective','If you are crazy about something, you are very enthusiastic about it. If you are not crazy about something, you do not like it.','He\'s still crazy about both his work and his hobbies.',4,'/kreɪzi/'),('tingle','24f391aa15fa90d0488a2ffecd9d80d2',NULL,'intransitive verb','When a part of your body tingles, you have a slight stinging feeling there.','The backs of his thighs tingled.\nIts effects on the nervous system include weakness, paralysis, and tingling in the hands and feet.',2,'/tɪŋgəl/'),('lament','2539044f4db7f2a7bd481576af23bb73',NULL,'countable noun','A lament is a poem, song, or piece of music which expresses sorrow that someone has died.','...Shelley\'s lament for the death of Keats.',3,'/ləmɛnt/'),('crazy','265df506a679f1dede02914a733cf251',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone or something as crazy, you think they are very foolish or strange.','People thought they were all crazy to try to make money from manufacturing.\nThe teenagers shook their long, black hair and gesticulated crazily.',4,'/kreɪzi/'),('preference','273420acae4ba718c0ee91feebd36860',NULL,'variable noun','If you have a preference for something, you would like to have or do that thing rather than something else.','It upset her when men revealed a preference for her sister.',4,'/prɛfərəns/'),('intense','27456a9df2e25dd3f6a4bf5f1bfc1fd0',NULL,'adjective','Intense is used to describe something that is very great or extreme in strength or degree.','He was sweating from the intense heat.\nStevens\'s murder was the result of a deep-seated and intense hatred.\nThe fast-food business is intensely competitive.\nThe attack was anticipated but its intensity came as a shock.',4,'/ɪntɛns/'),('resent','275bfafabcc6242860052e3f124ce94e',NULL,'transitive verb','If you resent someone or something, you feel bitter and angry about them.','She resents her mother for being so tough on her.',3,'/rɪzɛnt/'),('profane','27c2c59d1bb02acc3ba56b12734d2d28',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone profanes a religious belief or institution, they treat it with disrespect.','They have profaned the long upheld traditions of the church.',3,'/prəfeɪn/'),('misery','2805039f7007a0f2057f77fc47807b0f',NULL,'uncount noun','Misery is the way of life and unpleasant living conditions of people who are very poor.','A tiny, educated elite profited from the misery of their two million fellow countrymen.',3,'/mɪzəri/'),('flat','2836762dc6fbc5574c98a5df85cc7b8c',NULL,'countable noun','A flat is a tire that does not have enough air in it.','Then, after I finally got back on the highway, I developed a flat.',3,'/flæt/'),('trying','29686b1f4352b49569cead93ee0dee7c',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something or someone as trying, you mean that they are difficult to deal with and make you feel impatient or annoyed.','Support from those closest to you is vital in these trying times.',5,'/traɪɪŋ/'),('concern','297fb069e428ea3771b0e3333c403384',NULL,'phrase','If a company is a going concern, it is actually doing business, rather than having stopped trading or not yet having started trading.','The receivers will always prefer to sell a business as a going concern.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('flat','29899a82aac23cb4ace9893087da0952',NULL,'phrase','You use flat out to emphasize that something is completely the case.','That allegation is a flat-out lie.',3,'/flæt/'),('nervous','2993754a66f24f1679bdba878292e200',NULL,'adjective','A nervous person is very tense and easily upset.','She was apparently a very nervous woman, and that affected her career.',4,'/nɜrvəs/'),('touch','2a0e3d6eb6b40e917d1018548846ec0f',NULL,'transitive verb','If you touch something, you put your hand onto it in order to feel it or to make contact with it.','Her tiny hands gently touched my face.\nDon\'t touch!',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('sick','2a7b3fb3a817f31a7d9c1b2f637dfb75',NULL,'phrase','If you are out sick, you are not at work because you are sick.','That afternoon she was fired from her job as a nurse, because she\'d been out sick so much.',4,'/sɪk/'),('long','2abbfd77a43cdb758c154c46e1f3ea3a',NULL,'phrase','If you say that something will happen or happened before long, you mean that it will happen or it happened soon.','German interest rates will come down before long.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('inquisitive','2af0f6d1401ace13c3d1051b530a0da9',NULL,'adjective','An inquisitive person likes finding out about things, especially secret things.','Barrow had an inquisitive nature.',2,'/ɪnkwɪzɪtɪv/'),('furious','2b0faf6904611f1bced63d0a7213c672',NULL,'adjective','Furious is also used to describe something that is done with great energy, effort, speed, or violence.','A furious gunbattle ensued.\nOfficials worked furiously to repair the center court.',3,'/fyʊəriəs/'),('dread','2b11d464e13e750d0cd8941672a85120',NULL,'uncount noun','Dread is a feeling of great anxiety and fear about something that may happen.','She thought with dread of the cold winters to come.',3,'/drɛd/'),('zeal','2b1bce0f5b6c7ab45eea97e43bd27570',NULL,'uncount noun','Zeal is great enthusiasm, especially in connection with work, religion, or politics.','...his zeal for teaching.',3,'/zil/'),('enthusiasm','2bbae7ecf0c68365bbb1f0f39c663bea',NULL,'countable noun','An enthusiasm is an activity or subject that interests you very much and that you spend a lot of time on.','Draw him out about his current enthusiasms and future plans.',4,'/ɪnθuziæzəm/'),('content','2bd4b0852e54f68a532b2e7b1bb7fef3',NULL,'plural noun','The contents of a book are its different chapters and sections, usually shown in a list at the beginning of the book.','There is no Table of Contents.',5,'/kɒntɛnt/'),('arrogance','2bdad6bf80b0bc67f362ebf84679f386','arrogant',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('urge','2beeb57144b298c0465d19d70a39c5d4',NULL,'transitive verb','If you urge someone to do something, you try hard to persuade them to do it.','They urged Congress to approve plans for their reform program.',4,'/ɜrdʒ/'),('emotive','2c0df6ab352143cd903d311ac4080f1e',NULL,'adjective','An emotive situation or issue is likely to make people feel strong emotions.','Embryo research is an emotive issue.',2,'/ɪmoʊtɪv/'),('incense','2c3c4580e3656e526c3a71b7dd2b384d',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that something incenses you, you mean that it makes you extremely angry.','This proposal will incense conservation campaigners.\nMom was incensed at his lack of compassion.',3,'/ɪnsɛns/ /ɪnsɛns/'),('contrite','2c4e093d64886d295a888e507d2d2d78',NULL,'adjective','If you are contrite, you are very sorry because you have done something wrong.','',2,'/kəntraɪt/'),('halt','2c80a1614c4c09c0bdbd5a4ba8fcf723',NULL,'transitive verb','When a person or a vehicle halts or when something halts them, they stop moving in the direction they were going and stand still.','They halted at a short distance from the house.',3,'/hɔlt/'),('try','2d4b005a35baf9035bf50159e9256cef',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you try for something, you make an effort to get it or achieve it.','My partner and I have been trying for a baby for two years.',5,'/traɪ/'),('energetic','2d7b9cfb69753129c7847c58875c8515',NULL,'adjective','If you are energetic in what you do, you have a lot of enthusiasm and determination.','Ibrahim is 59, strong looking, enormously energetic and accomplished.\nHe had worked energetically all day on his new book.',3,'/ɛnərdʒɛtɪk/'),('insolent','2e3ea54e43e956c82b861fb1ca18e065',NULL,'adjective','If you say that someone is being insolent, you mean they are being rude to someone they ought to be respectful to.','...her insolent stare.',2,'/ɪnsələnt/'),('partial','2ecfbaecc1c99cecc074b8e07221ddc9',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is partial supports a particular person or thing, for example, in a competition or dispute, instead of being completely fair.','I might be accused of being partial.',4,'/pɑrʃəl/'),('incredible','2fbf383f9f80b3aafb74fc0ab38f9fe9',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something or someone as incredible, you like them very much or are impressed by them, because they are extremely or unusually good.','The wildflowers will be incredible after this rain.\nTheir father was incredibly good-looking.',3,'/ɪnkrɛdɪbəl/'),('hunger','30181ab4e64fa91b391d7b3d30b93dd0',NULL,'uncount noun','Hunger is the feeling of weakness or discomfort that you get when you need something to eat.','Hunger is the body\'s signal that levels of blood sugar are too low.',4,'/hʌŋgər/'),('long','3091e42866bfb5da6748c5866f2f3af9',NULL,'adjective','Something that is long measures a great distance from one end to the other.','...a long table.\nLucy was 27, with long dark hair.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('long','30db42fb9ab4aec232219b88765b53dc',NULL,'adjective','If someone has a long memory, they are able to remember things that happened far back in the past.','Mr. Assad, who has a long memory, will not have forgotten that meeting.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('strike','3205ed16cd48406342f4a765d29edf82',NULL,'transitive verb','When a clock strikes, its bells make a sound to indicate what the time is.','The clock struck nine.',4,'/straɪk/'),('strike','327e9655224a55aed49ae9078108ba8c',NULL,'transitive verb','If something strikes you as being a particular thing, it gives you the impression of being that thing.','He struck me as a very serious but friendly person.',4,'/straɪk/'),('terror','332e2e98afef66df21cd456576b0c5e1',NULL,'uncount noun','Terror is violence or the threat of violence, especially when it is used for political reasons.','...the war on terror.\nThe bomb attack on the capital could signal the start of a pre-election terror campaign.',4,'/tɛrər/'),('strike','343eb4a2936de800f12e6120b645d205',NULL,'transitive verb','If something strikes fear into people, it makes them very frightened or anxious.','If there is a single subject guaranteed to strike fear in the hearts of parents, it is drugs.',4,'/straɪk/'),('deplore','346d1612ff014e1970d571a64590b114',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that you deplore something, you think it is very wrong or immoral.','Muslim and Jewish leaders have issued statements deploring the violence and urging the United Nations to take action.',2,'/dɪplɔr/'),('partial','3557adc9136f018264f9cf82518edb38',NULL,'adjective','You use partial to refer to something that is not complete or whole.','He managed to reach a partial agreement with both republics.\n...a partial ban on the use of cars in the city.',4,'/pɑrʃəl/'),('halt','356df59c418ea032875654f9ab8d24dd',NULL,'phrase','If something such as growth, development, or activity comes or grinds to a halt or is brought to a halt, it stops completely.','Her political career came to a halt in December 1988.',3,'/hɔlt/'),('incentive','35c5e7dace2af6fa26c57dfe84fc49ae',NULL,'variable noun','If something is an incentive to do something, it encourages you to do it.','There is little or no incentive to adopt such measures.',3,'/ɪnsɛntɪv/'),('doubt','360eb5df2ac91f364c12c0646ca93159',NULL,'phrase','If you are in doubt about something, you feel unsure or uncertain about it.','He is in no doubt as to what is needed.',4,'/daʊt/'),('flat','369a85cd3697b3fd75a345b98ae692b8',NULL,'phrase','If an event or attempt falls flat or falls flat on its face, it is unsuccessful.','Liz meant it as a joke but it fell flat.',3,'/flæt/'),('horror','36c5a378607a6e470a656dce977cc5ce',NULL,'adjective','A horror film or story is intended to be very frightening.','...a psychological horror film.',4,'/hɔrər/'),('brisk','37eac561810c575dab6c6ad06a9988d3',NULL,'adjective','A brisk activity or action is done quickly and in an energetic way.','Taking a brisk walk can often induce a feeling of well-being.\nEve walked briskly down the corridor to her son\'s room.',3,'/brɪsk/'),('exalt','38179cfe8c28deeb98b227ef0cd714ee',NULL,'transitive verb','To exalt someone or something means to praise them very highly.','His work exalts all those virtues that we, as Americans, are taught to hold dear.',0,'/ɪgzɔlt/'),('touch','399a94d0a836187b7800b7cbb1272656',NULL,'uncount noun','Your sense of touch is your ability to tell what something is like when you feel it with your hands.','The evidence suggests that our sense of touch is programmed to diminish with age.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('abhor','39d160206955e94c3d397bc51ed519d3',NULL,'transitive verb','If you abhor something, you hate it very much, especially for moral reasons.','He was a man who abhorred violence and was deeply committed to reconciliation.',2,'/æbhɔr/'),('beat','3a3c592e5f14f96139e00f6e4ebcc30c',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone beats a record or achievement, they do better than it.','He was as eager as his Captain to beat the record.',4,'/bit/'),('beat','3abe34526a6e3ab36cf749dddf55d1cc',NULL,'transitive verb','If you beat someone in a competition or election, you defeat them.','In yesterday\'s game, Switzerland beat the United States two to one.',4,'/bit/'),('hail','3bcac85e23052c7647a0c64a5058bf93',NULL,'transitive verb','If a person, event, or achievement is hailed as important or successful, they are praised publicly.','Faulkner has been hailed as the greatest American novelist of his generation.',3,'/heɪl/'),('mean','3cb0f5e23153a4bcd2a11a9b5e11a220',NULL,'singular noun','The mean is a number that is the average of a set of numbers.','Take a hundred and twenty values and calculate the mean.',5,'/min/'),('scare','3dd8637e151537ed030752a3379fe9f3',NULL,'phrase','If you want to emphasize that something scares you a lot, you can say that it scares the hell out of you or scares the life out of you.','',3,'/skɛər/'),('flatter','3de10beb6e61a7802feef7db89104d3b',NULL,'transitive verb','If you flatter yourself that something good is the case, you believe that it is true, although others may disagree. If someone says to you \"you\'re flattering yourself\" or \"don\'t flatter yourself,\" they mean that they disagree with your good opinion of yourself.','I flatter myself that this campaign will put an end to the war.',3,'/flætər/'),('hail','3eb1a590264a53354a1db6fbc988c96d',NULL,'intransitive verb','When it hails, hail falls like rain from the sky.','It started to hail, huge great stones.',3,'/heɪl/'),('blessed','3edd19c70c7975bf976952fbfe6cff43',NULL,'adjective','You use blessed to describe something that you think is wonderful, and that you are grateful for or relieved about.','The birth of a live healthy baby is a truly blessed event.\n...a wall still blessedly warm from the day\'s sun.',3,'/blɛst/ /blɛsɪd/'),('starve','3fcfe6aaadbe35d64810a821afe93538',NULL,'transitive verb','To starve someone means not to give them any food.','He said the only alternative was to starve the people, and he said this could not be allowed to happen.',3,'/stɑrv/'),('touch','3ffe65a75751fd94dbd1282b6e4db4b3',NULL,'transitive verb','You say that you never touch something or that you have not touched something for a long time to emphasize that you never use it, or you have not used it for a long time.','He doesn\'t drink much and doesn\'t touch drugs.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('fury','40b8bafd1d1325dd051a660b6fed4e9f',NULL,'uncount noun','Fury is violent or very strong anger.','She screamed, her face distorted with fury and pain.',3,'/fyʊəri/'),('radical','40ff90588b0308443922d89a5dae2014',NULL,'adjective','Radical changes and differences are very important and great in degree.','The country needs a period of calm without more surges of radical change.\n...two large groups of people with radically different beliefs and cultures.',4,'/rædɪkəl/'),('realize','420d7c4db90ab18baec3b2e9cbafc0c7',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something realizes their potential, they do everything they are capable of doing, because they have been given the opportunity to do so.','The support systems to enable women to realize their potential at work are seriously inadequate.',4,'/riəlaɪz/'),('strain','4266093d1c78e118a42783b874bf9a1b',NULL,'transitive verb','When you strain food, you separate the liquid part of it from the solid parts.','Strain the stock and put it back into the pan.',4,'/streɪn/'),('partial','43698cff3af6fdf05d9b64b593f65345',NULL,'adjective','If you are partial to something, you like it.','He\'s partial to sporty women with blue eyes.\nMollie confesses she is rather partial to pink.',4,'/pɑrʃəl/'),('strain','4385b7a894506863e379e41ad03c2fd3',NULL,'transitive verb','If you strain a muscle, you injure it by using it too much or twisting it.','He strained his back during a practice session.',4,'/streɪn/'),('flat','43d545c87d394eeba4893d07e103092a',NULL,'countable noun','You can refer to one of the broad flat surfaces of an object as the flat of that object.','He slammed the counter with the flat of his hand.',3,'/flæt/'),('touch','43f22e8af15767d7be41873c50a7879e',NULL,'phrase','If you lose touch with something, you no longer have the latest news or information about it.','Their leaders have lost touch with what is happening in the country.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('upset','445437ed73dd8b01b75f01885c49d174',NULL,'transitive verb','If events upset something such as a procedure or a state of affairs, they cause it to go wrong.','Political problems could upset agreements between Moscow and Kabul.',4,'/ʌpsɛt/ /ʌpsɛt/'),('touch','4491d71b397e27a328bc60bf496ec1a3',NULL,'singular noun','If someone has a particular kind of touch, they have a particular way of doing something.','The dishes he produces all have a personal touch.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('starve','449aade571196e0c160aeed2a48b227a',NULL,'intransitive verb','If people starve, they suffer greatly from lack of food which sometimes leads to their death.','A number of the prisoners we saw are starving.\nIn the 1930s, millions of Ukrainians starved to death or were deported.',3,'/stɑrv/'),('strain','45be8a2ed7b336f028fe198ebc571281',NULL,'variable noun','If strain is put on an organization or system, it has to do more than it is able to do.','The prison service is already under considerable strain.',4,'/streɪn/'),('impulse','45dcd2186c8fac8afa67afbaa53ceefa',NULL,'countable noun','An impulse is a short electrical signal that is sent along a wire or nerve or through the air, usually as one of a series.','It works by sending a series of electrical impulses which are picked up by hi-tech sensors.',4,'/ɪmpʌls/'),('bore','4684f6492d0eaa20f5b0b57a786e835a',NULL,'singular noun','You can describe a situation as a bore when you find it annoying.','It\'s a bore to be sick, and the novelty of lying in bed all day wears off quickly.',3,'/bɔr/'),('elation','4706e727560cb5d613810da01ac91c50',NULL,'uncount noun','Elation is a feeling of great happiness and excitement about something that has happened.','His supporters have reacted to the news with elation.',2,'/ɪleɪʃən/'),('faint','479bc03f0e65513661baa2ac392a0c6c',NULL,'adjective','A faint attempt at something is one that is made without proper effort and with little enthusiasm.','Caroline made a faint attempt at a laugh.\nA faint smile crossed the Monsignor\'s face and faded quickly.\nJohn smiled faintly and shook his head.',3,'/feɪnt/'),('pensive','47db055c630c89da3f81a54786aad4fc',NULL,'adjective','If you are pensive, you are thinking deeply about something, especially something that worries you slightly.','He looked suddenly somber, pensive.\nAngela stared pensively out of the window at the rain.',2,'/pɛnsɪv/'),('flat','47fbde3ef61070831b7b167269035f89',NULL,'adjective','If you say that something happened, for example, in ten seconds flat or ten minutes flat, you are emphasizing that it happened surprisingly quickly and only took ten seconds or ten minutes.','You\'re sitting behind an engine that\'ll move you from 0 to 60mph in six seconds flat.',3,'/flæt/'),('desirous','4a1b9ff7ccd5728c3d53acca285a2717',NULL,'adjective','If you are desirous of doing something or desirous of something, you want to do it very much or want it very much.','The enemy is so desirous of peace that he will agree to any terms.',2,'/dɪzaɪərəs/'),('tortuous','4a1ddc6c2ea1424e779b162cf2188b7e',NULL,'adjective','A tortuous process or piece of writing is very long and complicated.','...these long and tortuous negotiations aimed at ending the conflict.',2,'/tɔrtʃuəs/'),('suspect','4b24f922ca8a0fda452eaa76f5373f5a',NULL,'adjective','Suspect things or people are ones that you think may be dangerous or may be less good or genuine than they appear.','Delegates evacuated the building when a suspect package was found.',4,'/səspɛkt/ /sʌspɛkt/'),('depression','4b8637a4e9101db70d4da496c00bd79b',NULL,'variable noun','Depression is a mental state in which you are sad and feel that you cannot enjoy anything, because your situation is so difficult and unpleasant.','Mr. Thomas was suffering from depression.',4,'/dɪprɛʃən/'),('gloomy','4f1547be62bee34b64f62dd379dcffb5',NULL,'adjective','If people are gloomy, they are unhappy and have no hope.','Miller is gloomy about the fate of the serious playwright in America.\nHe tells me gloomily that he has been called up for army service.',3,'/glumi/'),('tense','4f35ae8bc53df6dd3e878e26b80685ed',NULL,'transitive verb','If your muscles tense, if you tense, or if you tense your muscles, your muscles become tight and stiff, often because you are anxious or frightened.','Newman\'s stomach muscles tensed.',4,'/tɛns/'),('bore','4fb691f83a7e918045d3d5fa7c494199',NULL,'phrase','If someone or something bores you to tears, bores you to death, or bores you stiff, they bore you very much.','Monuments and museums bore him to tears.',3,'/bɔr/'),('pleasure','4fe5369f2695f8eb4e7d3461c450974c',NULL,'convention','If you meet someone for the first time, you can say, as a way of being polite, that it is a pleasure to meet them. You can also ask for the pleasure of someone\'s company as a polite and formal way of inviting them somewhere.','\"A pleasure to meet you, sir,\" he said.',4,'/plɛʒər/'),('fanaticism','503d12f87ed650bc05d9c5e1b574e6eb',NULL,'uncount noun','Fanaticism is fanatical behavior or the quality of being fanatical.','...a protest against intolerance and religious fanaticism.',2,'/fənætɪsɪzəm/'),('pleasure','508562f14c0167fc19b5f2683dfc0ba7',NULL,'uncount noun','If something gives you pleasure, you get a feeling of happiness, satisfaction, or enjoyment from it.','Watching sports gave him great pleasure.\nEverybody takes pleasure in eating.',4,'/plɛʒər/'),('long','5085d134fe312369ec7554196fbbb248',NULL,'phrase','If you say that something is the case as long as or so long as something else is the case, you mean that it is only the case if the second thing is the case.','He said he would still support them, as long as they didn\'t break the rules.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('exasperate','508d36b8bc9d7bc60c89f37bfd7e66d9',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something exasperates you, they annoy you and make you feel frustrated or upset.','The sheer futility of it all exasperates her.\nMahoney clenched his fist in exasperation.',1,'/ɪgzæspəreɪt/'),('hatred','5162efc10a4060cba86a8652aea13c16',NULL,'uncount noun','Hatred is an extremely strong feeling of dislike for someone or something.','Her hatred of them would never lead her to murder.',3,'/heɪtrɪd/'),('fishy','516ba1509f1e0e1697030950abac6cc1',NULL,'adjective','If you describe a situation as fishy, you feel that someone is not telling the truth or behaving completely honestly.','There seems to be something fishy going on.',2,'/fɪʃi/'),('touch','5193c7f7fc020907313d078cafe12ceb',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that you did not touch someone or something, you are emphasizing that you did not attack, harm or destroy them, especially when you have been accused of doing so.','Pearce remained adamant, saying \"I didn\'t touch him.\"',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('strain','51a510da1aca568d5ec44c9e68561e66',NULL,'singular noun','If you say that a situation is a strain, you mean that it makes you worried and tense.','I sometimes find it a strain to be responsible for the mortgage.',4,'/streɪn/'),('uproar','521604f9f146b182ffc6012cf93bf7ce',NULL,'uncount noun','If there is uproar, there is a lot of shouting and noise because people are very angry or upset about something.','The announcement caused an uproar in the crowd.',3,'/ʌprɔr/'),('tense','52304cdbf40f825ddbb3fe4f5b50c70c',NULL,'adjective','If your body is tense, your muscles are tight and not relaxed.','A bath can relax tense muscles.',4,'/tɛns/'),('boring','526865bf4053adb1a2ccdb347253409b',NULL,'adjective','Someone or something boring is so dull and uninteresting that they make people tired and impatient.','Not only are mothers not paid but also most of their boring or difficult work is unnoticed.',3,'/bɔrɪŋ/'),('flat','5314c73a4377baeface2ccda29eb3389',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something as flat, you mean that it is dull and not exciting or interesting.','The past few days have seemed comparatively flat and empty.',3,'/flæt/'),('stun','53d07e26c2176747365dd428336a73bf',NULL,'transitive verb','If something such as a blow on the head stuns you, it makes you unconscious or confused and unsteady.','Sam stood his ground and got a blow that stunned him.',2,'/stʌn/'),('astound','54c110d399b06ca8613a149c20eca39f',NULL,'transitive verb','If something astounds you, you are very surprised by it.','He used to astound his friends with feats of physical endurance.',2,'/əstaʊnd/'),('long','567bb4d3713672f3e7b2876687fc47fa',NULL,'adverb','You use long to ask or talk about amounts of time.','How long have you lived around here?\nHe has been on a diet for as long as any of his friends can remember.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('bore','569d8b84e7d4c04e00f3dc246c367fac',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something bores you, you find them dull and uninteresting.','Dickie bored him all through the meal with stories of the navy.',3,'/bɔr/'),('rage','571a658e16576d5cb398e428236ede64',NULL,'intransitive verb','You say that something powerful or unpleasant rages when it continues with great force or violence.','Train service was halted as the fire raged for more than four hours.',4,'/reɪdʒ/'),('realize','5764100f957ea0b1669774285a22a8fd',NULL,'transitive verb','When someone realizes a design or an idea, they make or organize something based on that design or idea.','I knew the technique that I would have to create in order to realize that structure.',4,'/riəlaɪz/'),('dismal','5766d40a5c7fe0701b40110dee8b28dd',NULL,'adjective','Something that is dismal is sad and depressing, especially in appearance.','The main part of the hospital is pretty dismal but the children\'s ward is really lively.',3,'/dɪzməl/'),('lament','5773977e0a528e45f9b64617896521c0',NULL,'transitive verb','If you lament something, you express your sadness, regret, or disappointment about it.','Ken began to lament the death of his only son.\nHe laments that people in Villa El Salvador are suspicious of the police.',3,'/ləmɛnt/'),('positive','57a629340d9eb2ecd1bacc82d9f96ba0',NULL,'adjective','If you are positive about things, you are hopeful and confident, and think of the good aspects of a situation rather than the bad ones.','Be positive about your future and get on with living a normal life.\nHer husband became much more positive and was soon back in full-time employment.\nYou really must try to start thinking positively.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('beat','57c6f9472118fa522795b0c733098d06',NULL,'intransitive verb','To beat on, at, or against something means to hit it hard, usually several times or continuously for a period of time.','There was dead silence but for a fly beating against the glass.\nNina managed to free herself and began beating at the flames with a pillow.',4,'/bit/'),('ecstasy','57eadd80b6a0eae897ef3f42fb421ace',NULL,'uncount noun','Ecstasy is an illegal drug that makes people feel happy and energetic.','The teenager died after taking ecstasy on her birthday.',3,'/ɛkstəsi/'),('crazy','584b6fc9a467e77f8f6253342c64c58d',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is crazy is insane.','If I sat home and worried about all this stuff, I\'d go crazy.',4,'/kreɪzi/'),('mean','593cdc252e9f7237cae219af259990af',NULL,'adjective','If you describe a person or animal as mean, you are saying that they are very bad-tempered and cruel.','The state\'s former commissioner of prisons once called Leonard the meanest man he\'d ever seen.',5,'/min/'),('long','593d27e82a3fec48633556ead31a8e4f',NULL,'phrase','If you say that someone won\'t be long, you mean that you think they will arrive or be back soon. If you say that it won\'t be long before something happens, you mean that you think it will happen soon.','\"What\'s happened to her?\"—\"I\'m sure she won\'t be long.\"',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('flat','5aa7ca570d9ad451d862dc41a23b0b2d',NULL,'phrase','If you fall flat on your face, you fall over.','A man walked in off the street and fell flat on his face, unconscious.',3,'/flæt/'),('ferocious','5acfa7fcdb26223f02aad872d245058f',NULL,'adjective','A ferocious war, argument, or other form of conflict involves a great deal of anger, bitterness, and determination.','Fighting has been ferocious.',3,'/fəroʊʃəs/'),('forlorn','5b437b315d66016e9944d24440ee01f5',NULL,'adjective','If someone is forlorn, they feel alone and unhappy.','One of the demonstrators, a young woman, sat forlorn on the sidewalk.',3,'/fɔrlɔrn/'),('long','5b4ba940debb57e7935724971b88ba9b',NULL,'phrase','The expression for long is used to mean \"for a great amount of time.\"','\"Did you live there?\"—\"Not for long.\"',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('long','5b4c6b72e50ea0a740f7a789048a745c',NULL,'transitive verb','If you long for something, you want it very much.','Steve longed for the good old days.\nI\'m longing to meet her.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('petrify','5b714f702f38d8cf4badd8434225f7fb',NULL,'transitive verb','If something petrifies you, it makes you feel very frightened.','Prison petrifies me and I don\'t want to go there.\nI found the climb absolutely petrifying.',1,'/pɛtrɪfaɪ/'),('desire','5b732d5fa92ca615fd273c3fca0ab4e1',NULL,'countable noun','A desire is a strong wish to do or have something.','I had a strong desire to help and care for people.',5,'/dɪzaɪər/'),('bore','5b83ed7490a9457bd00612a2b7b483ac',NULL,'transitive verb','If you bore a hole in something, you make a deep round hole in it using a special tool.','Get the special drill bit to bore the correct size hole for the job.',3,'/bɔr/'),('objective','5c7ab01711b4bda0da3886ee61e02a45',NULL,'countable noun','Your objective is what you are trying to achieve.','Our main objective was the recovery of the child safe and well.',4,'/əbdʒɛktɪv/'),('distress','5cc1ca8035b11a88a056a09ce4c80832',NULL,'uncount noun','Distress is the state of being in extreme danger and needing urgent help.','He expressed concern that the ship might be in distress.',3,'/dɪstrɛs/'),('hesitate','5d2bc33fbc68b1de3be8c5e1334d956f',NULL,'transitive verb','If you hesitate to do something, you delay doing it or are unwilling to do it, usually because you are not certain it would be right. If you do not hesitate to do something, you do it immediately.','Some parents hesitate to take these steps because they suspect that their child is exaggerating.',3,'/hɛzɪteɪt/'),('dubious','5d68974149a9dde4ed49f3d1a021f2d2',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something as dubious, you mean that you do not consider it to be completely honest, safe, or reliable.','This claim seems to us to be rather dubious.\nCarter was dubiously convicted of shooting three white men in a bar.',3,'/dubiəs/'),('cherish','5d6dcd895bf062eaacd63dfc7e28fbb3',NULL,'transitive verb','If you cherish someone or something, you take good care of them because you love them.','He genuinely loved and cherished her.\nHe described the picture as his most cherished possession.',3,'/tʃɛrɪʃ/'),('demur','5e15a8b10710525dd47172f28e69cbaa',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you demur, you say that you do not agree with something or will not do something that you have been asked to do.','The doctor demurred, but Piercey was insistent.',2,'/dɪmɜr/'),('positive','5e48d06c6a277a44ef9a4635a93a9127',NULL,'adjective','A positive number is greater than zero.','It\'s really a simple numbers game with negative and positive numbers.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('relieved','5e78de3d45099940d8d8c96dc7bc6752',NULL,'adjective','If you are relieved, you feel happy because something unpleasant has not happened or is no longer happening.','We are all relieved to be back home.',0,'/rɪlivd/'),('stodgy','5f7c6f351a4176a09d6ba9a2ce99aa36',NULL,'adjective','Stodgy food is very solid and heavy. It makes you feel very full, and is difficult to digest.','',2,'/stɒdʒi/'),('mean','606da8e36511c8595d39dff2f3b8c4ce',NULL,'transitive verb','If you ask someone what they mean, you are asking them to explain exactly what or who they are referring to or what they are intending to say.','Do you mean me?\nLet me illustrate what I mean with an old story.',5,'/min/'),('relieve','60dd68328d149963aef74e19d07e7951',NULL,'transitive verb','If something relieves an unpleasant feeling or situation, it makes it less unpleasant or causes it to disappear completely.','Drugs can relieve much of the pain.',0,'/rɪliv/'),('flat','613200ccab47b6d95c80212ba4a4e688',NULL,'adjective','Flat shoes have no heels or very low heels.','People wear slacks, sweaters, flat shoes, and all manner of casual attire for travel.',3,'/flæt/'),('indifferent','61d2d83bee01362d5036f8ec02c50edf',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something or someone as indifferent, you mean that their standard or quality is not very good, and often quite bad.','She had starred in several very indifferent movies.\n...a shoddy piece of work, poorly written, indifferently performed.',3,'/ɪndɪfərənt/'),('distress','6321ac73476c70ca25ccafbbc6d79974',NULL,'uncount noun','Distress is a state of extreme sorrow, suffering, or pain.','Jealousy causes distress and painful emotions.',3,'/dɪstrɛs/'),('pleasure','63a011b32818b8cabbd3f6f864d11a71',NULL,'convention','You can say \"It\'s a pleasure\" or \"My pleasure\" as a polite way of replying to someone who has just thanked you for doing something.','\"Thanks very much anyhow.\"—\"It\'s a pleasure.\"',4,'/plɛʒər/'),('profane','63c40a29b0472844429ee473b02ae534',NULL,'adjective','Profane behavior shows disrespect for a religion or religious things.','...profane language.',3,'/prəfeɪn/'),('intrude','6468214109d0aacab805773e03db73fa',NULL,'intransitive verb','If someone intrudes into a place, they go there even though they are not allowed to be there.','An American officer on the scene said no one had intruded into the space he was defending.',3,'/ɪntrud/'),('upset','64cc4fb5e511d56afcf5fd6a3e134796',NULL,'countable noun','A stomach upset is a slight sickness in your stomach caused by an infection or by something that you have eaten.','Paul was unwell last night with a stomach upset.',4,'/ʌpsɛt/ /ʌpsɛt/'),('curiosity','64f428a3a52bdc717bef988b4c3a4161',NULL,'uncount noun','Curiosity is a desire to know about something.','Ryle accepted more out of curiosity than anything else.\n...enthusiasm and genuine curiosity about the past.',4,'/kyʊəriɒsɪti/'),('solicitous','6511f864e62b971596024272b76f6849',NULL,'adjective','A person who is solicitous shows anxious concern for someone or something.','He was so solicitous of his guests.\nHe took her hand in greeting and asked solicitously how everything was.',2,'/səlɪsɪtəs/'),('bless','6536be60dcc0e092419a2a800c9390cb',NULL,'transitive verb','When someone such as a priest blesses people or things, he or she asks for God\'s favor and protection for them.','...asking for all present to bless this couple and their loving commitment to one another.',3,'/blɛs/'),('objective','65c987491ec3e79fcf9f67a35a669769',NULL,'adjective','Objective information is based on facts.','He had no objective evidence that anything extraordinary was happening.\nWe simply want to inform people objectively about events.\nThe poll, whose objectivity is open to question, gave the party a 39% share of the vote.',4,'/əbdʒɛktɪv/'),('sick','66a4328e201a8279f9d46a3a5d86502e',NULL,'adjective','If you are sick, you are ill. Sick usually means physically ill, but it can sometimes be used to mean mentally ill.','He\'s very sick. He needs medication.\nShe found herself with two small children, a sick husband, and no money.',4,'/sɪk/'),('miserable','66d8ac75cd08988465c255e94fde0130',NULL,'adjective','A miserable failure is a very great one.','The film was a miserable commercial failure both in Italy and in the United States.\nSome manage it. Some fail miserably.',3,'/mɪzərəbəl/'),('please','66e584e00a5b5aa5c10b4f4cc27fa3bc',NULL,'adverb','You say please when you are accepting something politely.','\"Tea?\"—\"Yes, please.\"',3,'/pliz/'),('exhaust','66fe132e0b8bce5abf919fb57bd87dbc',NULL,'transitive verb','If something exhausts you, it makes you so tired, either physically or mentally, that you have no energy left.','Don\'t exhaust him.\nShe was too exhausted and distressed to talk about the tragedy.\nIt was an exhausting schedule she had set herself.',3,'/ɪgzɔst/'),('touch','672d8831529a6134517f1ba754b2dbb9',NULL,'phrase','If you lose touch with someone, you gradually stop writing, telephoning, or visiting them.','In my job one tends to lose touch with friends.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('court','6734255b599d7512eb92521718a6a2e1',NULL,'reciprocal verb','If you are courting someone of the opposite sex, you spend a lot of time with them, because you are intending to get married. You can also say that a man and a woman are courting.','I was courting Billy at 19 and married him when I was 21.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('domineering','67d1f0354b415337ea8dcfe095d74aa9',NULL,'adjective','If you say that someone is domineering, you disapprove of them because you feel that they try to control other people without any consideration for their feelings or opinions.','Mick was stubborn and domineering with a very bad temper.',2,'/dɒmɪnɪərɪŋ/'),('intense','68055aa79fbf791f1a773c57ee135375',NULL,'adjective','If you describe the way someone looks at you as intense, you mean that they look at you very directly and seem to know what you are thinking or feeling.','I felt so self-conscious under Luke\'s mother\'s intense gaze.\nHe sipped his drink, staring intensely at me.',4,'/ɪntɛns/'),('dampen','680cff869bc1006bb7df04e3afc78ed1',NULL,'transitive verb','To dampen something such as someone\'s enthusiasm or excitement means to make it less lively or intense.','Nothing seems to dampen his perpetual enthusiasm.',2,'/dæmpən/'),('dread','68cdd9e717a308642bd73bc950aa8042',NULL,'transitive verb','If you dread something which may happen, you feel very anxious and unhappy about it because you think it will be unpleasant or upsetting.','I\'m dreading Christmas this year.\nI dreaded coming back, to be honest.',3,'/drɛd/'),('misery','69360ae377536f57de94fe1d68bfe942',NULL,'phrase','If you put an animal out of its misery, you kill it because it is sick or injured and cannot be cured or healed.','He notes grimly that the Watsons have called the vet to put their dog out of its misery.',3,'/mɪzəri/'),('scare','69b3e525771b68c93a7c5bce764af01e',NULL,'countable noun','A scare is a situation in which many people are afraid or worried because they think something dangerous is happening which will affect them all.','The news set off a continent-wide health scare.',3,'/skɛər/'),('realize','69bf129bb13cecb0cf2bb3b3635880c2',NULL,'transitive verb','If your hopes, desires, or fears are realized, the things that you hope for, desire, or fear actually happen.','All his worst fears were realized.\nIn Kravis\'s venomous tone he recognized the realization of his worst fears.',4,'/riəlaɪz/'),('tingle','6a00f45b7a3899399d0ce1ca256152e6',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you tingle with a feeling such as excitement, you feel it very strongly.','She tingled with excitement.',2,'/tɪŋgəl/'),('ferocious','6a05fc1c784392ed596e620657eb9365',NULL,'adjective','A ferocious animal, person, or action is very fierce and violent.','By its very nature a lion is ferocious.',3,'/fəroʊʃəs/'),('strike','6c485313a666677f97703c2973b7cded',NULL,'transitive verb','If you strike a pose or attitude, you put yourself in a particular position, for example when someone is taking your photograph.','She struck a pose, one hand on her hip and the other waving an imaginary cigarette.',4,'/straɪk/'),('chafe','6c49c65490dbb6d0d323d14161602966',NULL,'transitive verb','If your skin chafes or is chafed by something, it becomes sore as a result of something rubbing against it.','My shorts were chafing my thighs.\nHis wrists began to chafe against the cloth strips binding them.\nThe messenger bent and scratched at his knee where the strapping chafed.',2,'/tʃeɪf/'),('content','6cf5cf3b703a60b204229f2ee0031ad4',NULL,'singular noun','You can use content to refer to the amount or proportion of something that a substance contains.','Sunflower margarine has the same fat content as butter.',5,'/kɒntɛnt/'),('positive','6d65f5506d78f1ca1cc500a543077850',NULL,'adjective','If a medical or scientific test is positive, it shows that something has happened or is present.','If the test is positive, a course of antibiotics may be prescribed.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('cruel','6e1fa7ab92348671d87f9d3f9dc3505f',NULL,'adjective','A situation or event that is cruel is very harsh and causes people distress.','...struggling to survive in a cruel world with which they cannot cope.\nHis life has been cruelly shattered by an event not of his own making.',4,'/kruəl/'),('doubt','6ebffcd09c8271dae57e3c0104313366',NULL,'phrase','You use no doubt to emphasize that something seems certain or very likely to you.','The contract for this will no doubt be widely advertised.',4,'/daʊt/'),('motivate','6f7342e5e8b9d148ebeba3abcada1cca',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone motivates you to do something, they make you feel determined to do it.','How do you motivate people to work hard and efficiently?\nGiven parental motivation, we are optimistic about the ability of people to change.',0,'/moʊtɪveɪt/'),('beat','6fad27b2f992ad1d0733f71d046bcad9',NULL,'transitive verb','When a bird or insect beats its wings or when its wings beat, its wings move up and down.','Beating their wings they flew off.',4,'/bit/'),('brighten','7092761c9c9fcb91ac567b09b0656605',NULL,'transitive verb','When a light brightens a place or when a place brightens, it becomes brighter or lighter.','The sky above the ridge of mountains brightened.',2,'/braɪtən/'),('urge','70ab8ae43ff4fcbfaf7c49aba005ac19',NULL,'transitive verb','If you urge someone somewhere, you make them go there by touching them or talking to them.','He slipped his arm around her waist and urged her away from the window.',4,'/ɜrdʒ/'),('jealous','70ac7dcd05a85e9f4d8c5d37a21c0389',NULL,'adjective','If you are jealous of another person\'s possessions or qualities, you feel angry or bitter because you do not have them.','She was jealous of his wealth.\nGloria eyed them jealously.',3,'/dʒɛləs/'),('lament','71df7cc6fce157bcfa53d0e049896940',NULL,'countable noun','Someone\'s lament is an expression of their sadness, regret, or disappointment about something.','She spoke of the professional woman\'s lament that a woman\'s judgment is questioned more than a man\'s.',3,'/ləmɛnt/'),('overbearing','721d1e9401f2e5b66b82bbaa4474edb5',NULL,'adjective','An overbearing person tries to make other people do what he or she wants in an unpleasant and forceful way.','My husband can be a little overbearing with our son.',2,'/oʊvərbɛərɪŋ/'),('desire','72521191c68339889d7f471004ddd7b6',NULL,'transitive verb','If you desire something, you want it.','She had remarried and desired a child with her new husband.\nYou may find that just threatening this course of action will produce the desired effect.',5,'/dɪzaɪər/'),('outrage','73cb2124985fabe72396f313260765dd',NULL,'transitive verb','If you are outraged by something, it makes you extremely angry and shocked.','Many people have been outraged by some of the things that have been said.\nHe is truly outraged about what\'s happened to him.',3,'/aʊtreɪdʒ/ /aʊtreɪdʒ/'),('scruple','74fe33e35dcea7fe0ee6859a40cde57f',NULL,'variable noun','Scruples are moral principles or beliefs that make you unwilling to do something that seems wrong.','...a man with no moral scruples.',2,'/skrupəl/'),('mean','75128df553b692df0e732ad7e019ed60',NULL,'phrase','You can use \"I mean\" to introduce a statement, especially one that justifies something that you have just said.','I\'m sure he wouldn\'t mind. I mean, I was the one who asked him.',5,'/min/'),('brighten','751e1e48ed0ec47cbe0103def868e5a6',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something brightens a place, they make it more colorful and attractive.','Tubs planted with flowers brightened the area outside the door.',2,'/braɪtən/'),('miserable','754fce9ddc078d6549c1315eb25fb7b6',NULL,'adjective','If you are miserable, you are very unhappy.','I took a series of badly paid secretarial jobs which made me really miserable.\nHe looked miserably down at his plate.',3,'/mɪzərəbəl/'),('halt','759bc3749099567f542ce73eafec412c',NULL,'phrase','If someone or something comes to a halt, they stop moving.','The elevator creaked to a halt at the ground floor.',3,'/hɔlt/'),('torment','761e8dc8e3abb1152c26845b0e404570',NULL,'uncount noun','Torment is extreme suffering, usually mental suffering.','After years of turmoil and torment, she is finally at peace.',3,'/tɔrmɛnt/ /tɔrmɛnt/'),('panic','76537e822b94080ea643839f5757bd80',NULL,'uncount noun','Panic or a panic is a situation in which people are affected by a strong feeling of anxiety.','There was a moment of panic as it became clear just how vulnerable the nation was.\nI\'m in a panic about getting everything done in time.',4,'/pænɪk/'),('desire','76e8b35233e1a1d06e27b25e8e6d4c9f',NULL,'uncount noun','Desire for someone is a strong feeling of wanting to have sex with them.','It\'s common to lose your sexual desire when you have your first child.',5,'/dɪzaɪər/'),('hideous','7714b8d13145c3243420c6c412681dc9',NULL,'adjective','If you say that someone or something is hideous, you mean that they are very ugly or unattractive.','She saw a hideous face at the window and screamed.',3,'/hɪdiəs/'),('bias','772770792c85f5a1de755b0161a91e04',NULL,'variable noun','Bias is a tendency to prefer one person or thing to another, and to favor that person or thing.','...his desire to avoid the appearance of bias in favor of one candidate or another.',4,'/baɪəs/'),('impulse','77ab577d922a61391e70a5674a2abcaf',NULL,'adjective','An impulse buy or impulse purchase is something that you decide to buy when you see it, although you had not planned to buy it.','The curtains were an impulse buy.',4,'/ɪmpʌls/'),('outrage','77c76449e5ac734f2cd2402fe964cf98',NULL,'uncount noun','Outrage is an intense feeling of anger and shock.','The decision provoked outrage from women and human rights groups.',3,'/aʊtreɪdʒ/ /aʊtreɪdʒ/'),('suspense','7904d611416bbcbe58299903954b8bbc',NULL,'phrase','If you keep or leave someone in suspense, you deliberately delay telling them something that they are very eager to know about.','Keppler kept all his men in suspense until that morning before announcing which two would be going.',3,'/səspɛns/'),('eager','7944372413640a0447d7a1e38b99b83b',NULL,'adjective','If you look or sound eager, you look or sound as if you expect something interesting or enjoyable to happen.','Arty sneered at the crowd of eager faces around him.\n\"So what do you think will happen?\" he asked eagerly.\nIt was the voice of a woman speaking with breathless eagerness.',4,'/igər/'),('gratify','79c214fc57803af488a7226d62836b7b',NULL,'transitive verb','If you are gratified by something, it gives you pleasure or satisfaction.','Mr. Dambar was gratified by his response.\nWe took a chance and we\'ve won. It\'s very gratifying.\nHe is waiting for them to recognize him and eventually they do, much to his gratification.',2,'/grætɪfaɪ/'),('brighten','79f90b00f45852099fea6b4c9fa34749',NULL,'intransitive verb','If someone brightens or their face brightens, they suddenly look happier.','Seeing him, she seemed to brighten a little.',2,'/braɪtən/'),('gloom','7a79513bf046b468e0bfe30816974d31',NULL,'uncount noun','Gloom is a feeling of sadness and lack of hope.','...the deepening gloom over the economy.',3,'/glum/'),('court','7b1e255b523a4188630161c6c1b79490',NULL,'transitive verb','If you court something unpleasant such as disaster or unpopularity, you act in a way that makes it likely to happen.','If he thinks he can remain in power by force, he is courting disaster.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('rage','7b66bab6cd707b70108760d68a7c8a4a',NULL,'variable noun','Rage is strong anger that is difficult to control.','He was red-cheeked with rage.',4,'/reɪdʒ/'),('try','7bd70ec663b365f1cff466333e6d2ad2',NULL,'transitive verb','If you try to do something, you want to do it, and you take action which you hope will help you to do it.','He secretly tried to help her at work.\nDoes it annoy you if others don\'t seem to try hard enough?',5,'/traɪ/'),('suspicious','7beec467e08cbd3d6cf32f56e11e5676',NULL,'adjective','If you are suspicious of someone or something, you believe that they are probably involved in a crime or some dishonest activity.','Two officers on patrol became suspicious of two men in a car.',4,'/səspɪʃəs/'),('doubt','7c4be95175181fd676fd8a57c3e5435b',NULL,'convention','You say I doubt it as a response to a question or statement about something that you think is untrue or unlikely.','\"Somebody would have seen her.\"—\"I doubt it, not on Monday.\"',4,'/daʊt/'),('disgust','7d1445ec2441928647f1e24477728ea9',NULL,'uncount noun','Disgust is a feeling of very strong dislike or disapproval.','He spoke of his disgust at the incident.',3,'/dɪsgʌst/'),('mean','7d6cd7374a49d62b14f298ea80195ca4',NULL,'phrase','You use \"you mean\" in a question to check that you have understood what someone has said.','What accident? You mean Christina\'s?',5,'/min/'),('brisk','7d76100c542975ab7877c796d8a618fc',NULL,'adjective','If trade or business is brisk, things are being sold very quickly and a lot of money is being made.','Vendors were doing a brisk trade in souvenirs.\nA trader said gold sold briskly on the local market.',3,'/brɪsk/'),('beat','7ddcd2d8e2a8d09a08b262dfecc0b7ad',NULL,'transitive verb','If you beat a drum or similar instrument, you hit it in order to make a sound. You can also say that a drum beats.','When you beat the drum, you feel good.\n... drums beating and pipes playing.',4,'/bit/'),('stodgy','7e003447f08eeeac6d93871735e805a1',NULL,'adjective','If someone or something is stodgy, they are dull, unimaginative, and commonplace.','The company hasn\'t been able to shake off its image as stodgy and old-fashioned.',2,'/stɒdʒi/'),('hideous','7e04ac53d2c10955faf6240087db8216',NULL,'adjective','You can describe an event, experience, or action as hideous when you mean that it is very unpleasant, painful, or difficult to bear.','His family was subjected to a hideous attack by the gang.',3,'/hɪdiəs/'),('complaint','7e67dae452d9a57749adccca1a46b523',NULL,'countable noun','You can refer to an illness as a complaint, especially if it is not very serious.','Eczema is a common skin complaint which often runs in families.',4,'/kəmpleɪnt/'),('concern','7ea31e3e5f0d3ec7feb603a21a445dc8',NULL,'transitive verb','If a situation, event, or activity concerns you, it affects or involves you.','It was just a little unfinished business from my past, and it doesn\'t concern you at all.\nIt\'s a very stressful situation for everyone concerned.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('distressed','7edbcdfab52bf3159c15b1c1f1e916d3',NULL,'adjective','If someone is distressed, they are upset or worried.','I feel very alone and distressed about my problem.',3,'/dɪstrɛst/'),('vex','80046f1c1e87e8c5de0a99bc37d26a92',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something vexes you, they make you feel annoyed, puzzled, and frustrated.','It vexed me to think of others gossiping behind my back.\nExporters, farmers and industrialists alike are vexed and blame the government.\nThere remains, however, another and more vexing problem.',2,'/vɛks/'),('torment','800d98c88955c886fdb219aaa94e2160',NULL,'transitive verb','If something torments you, it causes you extreme mental suffering.','At times the memories returned to torment her.',3,'/tɔrmɛnt/ /tɔrmɛnt/'),('incredible','8025abf3d39553e26accda568240059f',NULL,'adjective','If you say that something is incredible, you mean that it is very unusual or surprising, and you cannot believe it is really true, although it may be.','It seemed incredible that people would still want to play football during a war.\nIncredibly, some people don\'t like the name.',3,'/ɪnkrɛdɪbəl/'),('long','80f349e14d7a355b7df6d35402b28e9e',NULL,'adjective','A long event or period of time lasts for a great amount of time or takes a great amount of time.','We had a long meeting with the attorney general.\nShe is planning a long vacation in Europe.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('sick','8111a656402fd3ce636dec791c7dfe5a',NULL,'adjective','If you say that you are sick of something or sick and tired of it, you are emphasizing that you are very annoyed by it and want it to stop.','I am sick and tired of hearing all these people moaning.',4,'/sɪk/'),('cower','812dbe26265293417d89b5c3ab1af817',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you cower, you bend forward and downward because you are very frightened.','The hostages cowered in their seats.',2,'/kaʊər/'),('depress','818aef0ca17b5a53a2a81ea7a73c6c8e',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something depresses you, they make you feel sad and disappointed.','I must admit the state of the country depresses me.',2,'/dɪprɛs/'),('languid','81c7b02b7204572d377e3af5de177a8f',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone as languid, you mean that they show little energy or interest and are very slow and casual in their movements.','He\'s a large, languid man with a round and impassive face.\nWe sat about languidly after dinner.',2,'/læŋgwɪd/'),('malice','820991dbbb3c042f2d9da2fead674798',NULL,'uncount noun','Malice is behavior that is intended to harm people or their reputations, or cause them embarrassment and upset.','There was a strong current of malice in many of his portraits.',3,'/mælɪs/'),('doubt','821689cac6ff5489207db129e0d7dafe',NULL,'phrase','If you say that something is true without doubt or without a doubt, you are emphasizing that it is definitely true.','This was without doubt the most interesting situation that Amanda had ever found herself in.',4,'/daʊt/'),('flatter','82324236ea135faa433de5e310b9d966',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone flatters you, they praise you in an exaggerated way that is not sincere, because they want to please you or to persuade you to do something.','I knew she was just flattering me.',3,'/flætər/'),('hail','82ed71229d97343f928561ffdb423153',NULL,'transitive verb','If you hail a taxi, you wave at it in order to stop it because you want the driver to take you somewhere.','I hurried away to hail a taxi.',3,'/heɪl/'),('fret','82efeb8400c637ae71c52e1fbaa0c6c4',NULL,'transitive verb','If you fret about something, you worry about it.','I was working all hours and constantly fretting about everyone else\'s problems.\nBut congressional staffers fret that the project will eventually cost billions more.',2,'/frɛt/'),('sensuous','837841df830420580151bb949ea8d599',NULL,'adjective','Someone or something that is sensuous shows or suggests a great liking for sexual pleasure.','...his sensuous young mistress, Marie-Therese.\n...wide sensuous lips.\nThe nose was straight, the mouth sensuously wide and full.',3,'/sɛnʃuəs/'),('impatient','837b6d209696d035a35c671f4ecb4886',NULL,'adjective','If you are impatient to do something or impatient for something to happen, you are eager to do it or for it to happen and do not want to wait.','He didn\'t want to tell Mr. Morrisson why he was impatient to get home.\nShe showed impatience to continue the climb.',3,'/ɪmpeɪʃənt/'),('desperate','83a9cd8919d877501534e5723bfce71b',NULL,'adjective','A desperate situation is very difficult, serious, or dangerous.','India\'s United Nations ambassador said the situation is desperate.',4,'/dɛspərɪt/'),('fanatic','8409047125a2cc002303509bc54542e2',NULL,'countable noun','If you describe someone as a fanatic, you disapprove of them because you consider their behavior or opinions to be very extreme, for example, in the way they support particular religious or political ideas.','I am not a religious fanatic but I am a Christian.',2,'/fənætɪk/'),('please','8422b2ba0bb4fdd234a1944e30ae262b',NULL,'adverb','You say please when you are politely asking or inviting someone to do something.','Can you help us please?\nPlease come in.\nCan we have the bill please?',3,'/pliz/'),('brighten','848bc63d9e4a442146a60e5f91da965b',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something brightens a situation or the situation brightens, it becomes more pleasant, enjoyable, or favorable.','That does not do much to brighten the prospects of kids in the city.',2,'/braɪtən/'),('malevolent','84cfcb7a727e66ff4f09b529442e5712',NULL,'adjective','A malevolent person deliberately tries to cause harm or evil.','Her stare was malevolent, her mouth a thin line.\n...a rare streak of malevolence.\nMark watched him malevolently.',3,'/mælɛvələnt/'),('bore','85263ddba885cf2dc71b964a87082c03',NULL,'countable noun','You describe someone as a bore when you think that they talk in a very uninteresting way.','There is every reason why I shouldn\'t enjoy his company – he\'s a bore and a fool.',3,'/bɔr/'),('hail','8531fbe5f027b346f7e7500e4f7de23b',NULL,'intransitive verb','Someone who hails from a particular place was born there or lives there.','He hails from Memphis.',3,'/heɪl/'),('strike','85e4b3fe1079f5d3d01f6e0757cd3b2a',NULL,'transitive verb','If something that is falling or moving strikes something, it hits it.','His head struck the bottom when he dived into the 6 ft end of the pool.\nOne 16-inch shell struck the control tower.',4,'/straɪk/'),('mean','85f58a0ee9472ed17fa55945e4fd1a53',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that someone did not mean any harm, offense, or disrespect, you are saying that they did not intend to upset or offend people or to cause problems, even though they may in fact have done so.','I\'m sure he didn\'t mean any harm.',5,'/min/'),('cruel','867d0d466b01f6a6c6a7c2fd5d86f432',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is cruel deliberately causes pain or distress to people or animals.','Children can be so cruel.\nDouglas was often cruelly tormented by jealous siblings.',4,'/kruəl/'),('crazy','872a0ad9e9fb6ead5a2302dc5904daec',NULL,'adjective','Crazy is also a noun.','Outside, mumbling, was one of New York\'s ever-present crazies.\nSports-crazy Coloradans will buy tickets to anything.',4,'/kreɪzi/'),('intuition','8781b7cd9f9dd2d302b3b17119311696',NULL,'variable noun','Your intuition or your intuitions are unexplained feelings that something is true even when you have no evidence or proof of it.','Her intuition was telling her that something was wrong.',3,'/ɪntuɪʃən/'),('bless','878e16d00c7309b2ba74e2f967dae7bf',NULL,'convention','Bless is used in expressions such as \"God bless\" or \"bless you\" to express affection, thanks, or good wishes.','\"Bless you, Eva,\" he whispered.',3,'/blɛs/'),('bliss','87a269b4d730bd3c737b4d842b0f7477',NULL,'uncount noun','Bliss is a state of complete happiness.','It was a scene of such domestic bliss.',3,'/blɪs/'),('try','87a7541d7898719e2cdd1bd404229248',NULL,'transitive verb','If you try a door or window, you try to open it.','Bob tried the door. To his surprise it opened.',5,'/traɪ/'),('devote','8854721faf8294b659d842c614d501c0',NULL,'transitive verb','If you devote yourself, your time, or your energy to something, you spend all or most of your time or energy on it.','He decided to devote the rest of his life to scientific investigation.\nConsiderable resources have been devoted to proving him a liar.',4,'/dɪvoʊt/'),('impulse','88674b59953b58d269b342fbe271ac85',NULL,'variable noun','An impulse is a sudden desire to do something.','Unable to resist the impulse, he glanced at the sea again.',4,'/ɪmpʌls/'),('grievance','888b73ca392b72f6d5821c42d1cb2e60',NULL,'variable noun','If you have a grievance about something that has happened or been done, you believe that it was unfair.','They had a legitimate grievance.\nThe main grievance of the drivers is the imposition of higher fees for driver\'s licenses.',3,'/grivəns/'),('gleeful','895769feb8c6caef02ceef64e8066189',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is gleeful is happy and excited, often because of someone else\'s bad luck.','He took an almost gleeful delight in showing how wrong they can be.\nI spent the rest of their visit gleefully boring them with tedious details.',2,'/glifʊl/'),('tense','8969ecaf283eb0112c76f651f05e911d',NULL,'adjective','A tense situation or period of time is one that makes people anxious, because they do not know what is going to happen next.','This gesture of goodwill did little to improve the tense atmosphere at the talks.',4,'/tɛns/'),('touch','8986664a96d6c132cd88918de6ce3767',NULL,'countable noun','A touch is a detail which is added to something to improve it.','They called the event \"a tribute to heroes,\" which was a nice touch.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('tedious','898c89bce339f57cded9a05f24bb3956',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something such as a job, task, or situation as tedious, you mean it is boring and frustrating.','Such lists are long and tedious to read.\n...the most tediously boring aspects of international relations.',3,'/tidiəs/'),('mean','899c9913e3728234d6c2b467c8f77b9a',NULL,'phrase','You say I mean when correcting something that you have just said.','It was law or classics – I mean English or classics.',5,'/min/'),('exalted','89f6bd989f29b5e108c48d96f98bbacd',NULL,'adjective','Someone or something that is at an exalted level is at a very high level, especially with regard to rank or importance.','You must decide how to make the best use of your exalted position.',0,'/ɪgzɔltɪd/'),('loath','8ab251e5d3195d4f0c23e800f434fb2a',NULL,'adjective','If you are loath to do something, you do not want to do it.','Sensing he held the advantage, Mr. Danbar was loath to change the subject.',2,'/loʊθ/'),('misery','8ab57da1d495b11f71775689442f389e',NULL,'phrase','If you put someone out of their misery, you tell them something that they are very anxious to know.','Please put me out of my misery. How do you do it?',3,'/mɪzəri/'),('panic','8ac1fe19e87a6e142d9f319ba2c1f49b',NULL,'transitive verb','If you panic or if someone panics you, you suddenly feel anxious or afraid, and act quickly and without thinking carefully.','Guests panicked and screamed when the bomb exploded.\nThe unexpected and sudden memory briefly panicked her.',4,'/pænɪk/'),('listless','8b03111d4a6077ad6738811dabb02b4b',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is listless has no energy or enthusiasm.','He was listless and pale and wouldn\'t eat much.\nUsually, you would just sit listlessly, too hot to do anything else.',2,'/lɪstlɪs/'),('boredom','8b27d875245552562a209503070ed8a2',NULL,'uncount noun','Boredom is the state of being bored.','He had given up attending lectures out of sheer boredom.',3,'/bɔrdəm/'),('nostalgia','8b61926a354616f5191273dadfeb831b',NULL,'uncount noun','Nostalgia is an affectionate feeling you have for the past, especially for a particularly happy time.','He might be influenced by nostalgia for the surroundings of his happy youth.',3,'/nɒstældʒə/'),('provoke','8b9dbdd99c3cc3a3ab309d862c260cfc',NULL,'transitive verb','If something provokes a reaction, it causes it.','His election success has provoked a shocked reaction.',3,'/prəvoʊk/'),('flat','8bcff0fd3db958d96ae4e4ae21440da3',NULL,'adjective','Flat is used after a letter representing a musical note to show that the note should be played or sung half a tone lower than the note which otherwise matches that letter. Flat is often represented by the symbol♭after the letter.','...Schubert\'s B flat Piano Trio (Opus 99).',3,'/flæt/'),('crave','8cbbc3bf3d796cd85d827190b5b35196',NULL,'transitive verb','If you crave something, you want to have it very much.','There may be certain times of day when smokers crave their cigarette.\n...a craving for sugar.',3,'/kreɪv/'),('strike','8d0bebc6f88135ab9b5f9725509626af',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone strikes oil or gold, they discover it in the ground as a result of mining or drilling.','Oil industry sources say that Marathon Oil Company has struck oil in Syria.',4,'/straɪk/'),('court','8df543914b82ddeace5d17252ef2d887',NULL,'countable noun','The court of a king or queen is the place where he or she lives and carries out ceremonial or administrative duties.','She came to visit England, where she was presented at the court of James I.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('misgiving','8e755ce818ce325ede0e4680f3cf680c',NULL,'variable noun','If you have misgivings about something that is being suggested or done, you feel that it is not quite right, and are worried that it may have unwanted results.','She had some misgivings about what she was about to do.',2,'/mɪsgɪvɪŋ/'),('exultant','8f55ffef8297aa4b39a88121254569cb',NULL,'adjective','If you are exultant, you feel very happy and proud about something you have done.','An exultant party leader said: \"He will be an excellent MP.\"\n\"We cannot lose the war!\" he shouted exultantly.',2,'/ɪgzʌltənt/'),('aversion','906e8c7b5d1986a9382a1a15cf0e7d33',NULL,'variable noun','If you have an aversion to someone or something, you dislike them very much.','Many people have a natural and emotional aversion to insects.',3,'/əvɜrʒən/'),('avid','9118eeaf49b4da080e7bf1256f399979',NULL,'adjective','You use avid to describe someone who is very enthusiastic about something that they do.','He misses not having enough books because he\'s an avid reader.\nThank you for a most entertaining magazine, which I read avidly each month.',3,'/ævɪd/'),('insane','9124d34ac861d707fff12e7bbd4bdeb6',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is insane is severely mentally ill.','Some people simply can\'t take it and they just go insane.',3,'/ɪnseɪn/'),('intrude','913b429ac5ff63f739515bef1ec2daf6',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you say that someone is intruding into a particular place or situation, you mean that they are not wanted or welcome there.','The press has been blamed for intruding into people\'s personal lives in an unacceptable way.',3,'/ɪntrud/'),('nervous','9147905340d74e18a034b746acb0baca',NULL,'adjective','If someone is nervous, they are frightened or worried about something that is happening or might happen, and show this in their behavior.','The party has become deeply nervous about its prospects of winning the next election.\nBrunhilde stood up nervously as the men came into the room.\nI smiled warmly so he wouldn\'t see my nervousness.',4,'/nɜrvəs/'),('beat','91a32db468e992bc49035c2a5ddb6000',NULL,'countable noun','In music, a beat is a unit of measurement. The number of beats in a measure of a piece of music is indicated by two numbers at the beginning of the piece.','It\'s got four beats to a measure.',4,'/bit/'),('cherish','91cba82d4def922b55affd5f684f28a9',NULL,'transitive verb','If you cherish something such as a hope or a pleasant memory, you keep it in your mind for a long period of time.','The president will cherish the memory of this visit to Ohio.\n...the cherished dream of a world without wars.',3,'/tʃɛrɪʃ/'),('terror','927d6a7e8ed3a468f1b0cf16b3bac09b',NULL,'uncount noun','Terror is very great fear.','I shook with terror whenever I was about to fly in a plane.',4,'/tɛrər/'),('curiosity','92afb475fd0ea0ebaa443fb896504ed2',NULL,'countable noun','A curiosity is something that is unusual, interesting, and fairly rare.','There is much to see in the way of castles, curiosities, and museums.',4,'/kyʊəriɒsɪti/'),('intimidate','92b80702dc80858a0ba21d284439e3ca',NULL,'transitive verb','If you intimidate someone, you deliberately make them frightened enough to do what you want them to do.','Jones had set out to intimidate and dominate Paul.\n...an inquiry into allegations of intimidation during last week\'s vote.',3,'/ɪntɪmɪdeɪt/'),('intrude','9317dee5fb8707bad12563c89af702a3',NULL,'intransitive verb','If something intrudes on your mood or your life, it disturbs it or has an unwanted effect on it.','Do you feel anxious when unforeseen incidents intrude on your day?',3,'/ɪntrud/'),('complaint','93a0d28af6277f477e40b11f456d3861',NULL,'variable noun','A complaint is a statement in which you express your dissatisfaction with a situation.','There\'s been a record number of complaints about the standard of service.\nPeople have been reluctant to make formal complaints to the police.',4,'/kəmpleɪnt/'),('pleasure','947ec4e47178c457ced3ad1cb161eec5',NULL,'uncount noun','Pleasure is the activity of enjoying yourself, especially rather than working or doing what you have a duty to do.','He mixed business and pleasure in a perfect and dynamic way.',4,'/plɛʒər/'),('strike','9487ec69f68136cfc334724170571a91',NULL,'transitive verb','If something such as an illness or disaster strikes, it suddenly happens.','Fed officials continued to insist that the dollar would soon return to stability but disaster struck.\nA moderate earthquake struck the northeastern United States early on Saturday.',4,'/straɪk/'),('grouchy','94efd910a7e2513ff2eb086bf30fca69',NULL,'adjective','If someone is grouchy, they are very bad-tempered and complain a lot.','Your grandmother has nothing to stop her from being bored, grouchy, and lonely.',2,'/graʊtʃi/'),('trepidation','9506a00e077c17b1dbd9617d31ac1c94',NULL,'uncount noun','Trepidation is fear or anxiety about something that you are going to do or experience.','It was with some trepidation that I viewed the prospect of cycling across Uganda.',2,'/trɛpɪdeɪʃən/'),('striking','9608bd06a561d79511ca86eff61c89cb',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is striking is very attractive, in a noticeable way.','She was a striking woman with long blonde hair.',4,'/straɪkɪŋ/'),('devoted','964987336346633ead07542b164f9377',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is devoted to a person loves that person very much.','...a loving and devoted husband.',4,'/dɪvoʊtɪd/'),('menace','97cd06985c2d1694797e7b1f5491ef95',NULL,'countable noun','You can refer to someone or something as a menace when you want to say that they cause you trouble or annoyance.','You\'re a menace to my privacy, Kenton.',3,'/mɛnɪs/'),('nervous','983f7f089c6e4df2242fe6d0574fc74d',NULL,'adjective','A nervous illness or condition is one that affects your emotions and your mental state.','The number of nervous disorders was rising in the region.',4,'/nɜrvəs/'),('astonish','98bfe5350845410b39d52b9adc335589',NULL,'transitive verb','If something or someone astonishes you, they surprise you very much.','My news will astonish you.',0,'/əstɒnɪʃ/'),('dismay','98d84d86c04c7b37ee68e9f49d229736',NULL,'transitive verb','If you are dismayed by something, it makes you feel afraid, worried, or sad.','The committee was dismayed by what it had been told.\nHe was dismayed at the cynicism of the youngsters.',3,'/dɪsmeɪ/'),('suspicion','9968e9356afd0c9adc54661a15a1a774',NULL,'variable noun','If there is suspicion of someone or something, people do not trust them or consider them to be reliable.','This tendency in his thought is deepened by his suspicion of all Utopian political programs.',4,'/səspɪʃən/'),('flat','99b063b1814347ed989938f730691e32',NULL,'adjective','If you have flat feet, the arches of your feet are too low.','The condition of flat feet runs in families.',3,'/flæt/'),('long','99c2b501e29a13739df00d02acb5a69a',NULL,'phrase','You can say so long as an informal way of saying goodbye.','Well, so long, pal, see you around.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('contemptuous','99ef573fb83315fdac4cce587659d4ae',NULL,'adjective','If you are contemptuous of someone or something, you do not like or respect them at all.','He was contemptuous of the poor.\nHe\'s openly contemptuous of all the major political parties.',3,'/kəntɛmptʃuəs/'),('eager','9a172b84950d42a22e3c6dfa5d97a561',NULL,'adjective','If you are eager to do or have something, you want to do or have it very much.','Robert was eager to talk about life in the Army.\nWhen my own son was five years old, I became eager for another baby.\n...an eagerness to learn.',4,'/igər/'),('indifferent','9a263e973ebc08983c2b5e2e958bb023',NULL,'adjective','If you accuse someone of being indifferent to something, you mean that they have a complete lack of interest in it.','People have become indifferent to the suffering of others.\n\"Not that it matters,\" said Trujillo indifferently.',3,'/ɪndɪfərənt/'),('long','9a6d703293df5a35394e8aa2c99814bc',NULL,'adjective','A long speech, book, movie, or list contains a lot of information or a lot of items and takes a lot of time to listen to, read, watch, or deal with.','He was making quite a long speech.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('depression','9af4ad38381e6e9c196a4b2e8f5f17e5',NULL,'countable noun','A depression is a mass of air that has a low pressure and that often causes rain.','To the northwest lies a depression with clouds and rain.',4,'/dɪprɛʃən/'),('flat','9b6ee2597843e782009b864c91208a4a',NULL,'countable noun','A low flat area of uncultivated land, especially an area where the ground is soft and wet, can be referred to as flats or a flat.','The salt marshes and mud flats attract large numbers of waterfowl.',3,'/flæt/'),('touch','9b8e0905b690e96d944a3a1d7c1d49cf',NULL,'phrase','You use at the touch of in expressions such as at the touch of a button and at the touch of a key to indicate that something is possible by simply touching a switch or one of the keys of a keyboard.','Staff will be able to trace calls at the touch of a button.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('faint','9b8eb7cff168e0010add368ab496a631',NULL,'adjective','A faint sound, color, mark, feeling, or quality has very little strength or intensity.','He became aware of the soft, faint sounds of water dripping.\nThere was still the faint hope deep within him that she might never need to know.\nHe was already asleep in the bed, which smelled faintly of mildew.',3,'/feɪnt/'),('misery','9d131e28274522858c18efc64acecbdb',NULL,'phrase','If someone makes your life a misery, they behave in an unpleasant way towards you over a period of time and make you very unhappy.','I would really like living here if it wasn\'t for the gangs of kids who make our lives a misery.',3,'/mɪzəri/'),('grieve','9d754ab5583b20d46705f6d35c557eb6',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you grieve over something, especially someone\'s death, you feel very sad about it.','He\'s grieving over his dead wife and son.\nI didn\'t have any time to grieve.',3,'/griv/'),('sicken','9dbd2b595f45ac5a883c6b82b328134a',NULL,'transitive verb','If something sickens you, it makes you feel disgusted.','The notion that art should be controlled by intellectuals sickened him.',2,'/sɪkən/'),('ravish','9e126d33865f29ac24d5f71a0dd0a026',NULL,'transitive verb','If a woman is ravished by a man, she is raped by him.','She\'ll never know how close she came to being dragged off and ravished.',2,'/rævɪʃ/'),('grieved','9e94747145728a38eee0a2c97d367e9a','grieve',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('exhaust','9eee5089ca801f4a66f585445aef8486',NULL,'countable noun','The exhaust is the same as the   exhaust pipe.','',3,'/ɪgzɔst/'),('desperate','9f18cc1b140f09d320144e7dd08a2bb1',NULL,'adjective','If you are desperate for something or desperate to do something, you want or need it very much indeed.','They\'d been married nearly four years and June was desperate to start a family.\nHe was a boy who desperately needed affection.',4,'/dɛspərɪt/'),('suspect','9f40b0091d1315622fdb75813d00044b',NULL,'transitive verb','You use suspect when you are stating something that you believe is probably true, in order to make it sound less strong or direct.','I suspect they were right.\nThe above complaints are, I suspect, just the tip of the iceberg.',4,'/səspɛkt/ /sʌspɛkt/'),('tense','9f7c1835b4aba328fc090d6c23cdf41a',NULL,'countable noun','The tense of a verb group is its form, which usually shows whether you are referring to past, present, or future time.','It was as though Corinne was already dead: they were speaking of her in the past tense.',4,'/tɛns/'),('mean','9f80cbf3b527980ec61d386f69a5b5c5',NULL,'transitive verb','If you mean to do something, you intend or plan to do it.','Summer is the perfect time to catch up on the new books you meant to read.',5,'/min/'),('strike','a04073061fbce90e25a0f2da368b27d4',NULL,'transitive verb','If you strike someone or something, you deliberately hit them.','She took two quick steps forward and struck him across the mouth.\nIt is impossible to say who struck the fatal blow.',4,'/straɪk/'),('flounder','a071b787bd2f36f0c4acb7b2deb64044',NULL,'intransitive verb','If something is floundering, it has many problems and may soon fail completely.','What a pity that his career was left to flounder.',2,'/flaʊndər/'),('flat','a1b20d4121cbdcb62659145a06f0f5cd',NULL,'adjective','A flat object is not very tall or deep in relation to its length and width.','Ellen is walking down the drive with a square flat box balanced on one hand.',3,'/flæt/'),('daze','a1e82c34ef7c85a32eb7963cb92ef1f6',NULL,'singular noun','If someone is in a daze, they are feeling confused and unable to think clearly, often because they have had a shock or surprise.','For an hour I was walking around in a daze.',2,'/deɪz/'),('hunger','a34d651977478aa516ccd35979957820',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you say that someone hungers for something or hungers after it, you are emphasizing that they want it very much.','But Jules was not eager for classroom learning, he hungered for adventure.',4,'/hʌŋgər/'),('concern','a3a9be2cc3d588936a9a9c934b171ac3',NULL,'variable noun','Concernfor someone is a feeling that you want them to be happy, safe, and well. If you do something out of concern for someone, you do it because you want them to be happy, safe, and well.','Without her care and concern, he had no chance at all.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('intense','a3ced6c04a5d111e111492af03dfdaff',NULL,'adjective','If you describe a person as intense, you mean that they appear to concentrate very hard on everything that they do, and they feel their emotions very strongly.','I know he\'s an intense player, but he does enjoy what he\'s doing.\nHis intensity and the ferocity of his feelings alarmed me.',4,'/ɪntɛns/'),('suspicion','a432c8b3d3bbceca0ba8fa0afccfc8fa',NULL,'variable noun','Suspicion or a suspicion is a belief or feeling that someone has committed a crime or done something wrong.','There was a suspicion that this runner attempted to avoid the procedures for drug testing.\nThe police said their suspicions were aroused because Mr. Owens had other marks on his body.',4,'/səspɪʃən/'),('sick','a438fa442adf011a20830bbdc836611a',NULL,'phrase','If you say that something or someone makes you sick, you mean that they make you feel angry or disgusted.','It makes me sick that this wasn\'t disclosed.',4,'/sɪk/'),('content','a4672e49d36a878f50cdea5a51df90f5',NULL,'plural noun','The contents of a container such as a bottle, box, or room are the things that are inside it.','Empty the contents of the pan into the sieve.',5,'/kɒntɛnt/'),('hunger','a493fa6cf2d3d3217709cebce17a04e7',NULL,'singular noun','If you have a hunger for something, you want or need it very much.','Geffen has a hunger for success that seems bottomless.',4,'/hʌŋgər/'),('concern','a52a337038f48b6b75315d39f79e7345',NULL,'transitive verb','If something concerns you, it worries you.','The growing number of people seeking refuge in Thailand is beginning to concern Western aid agencies.\nAcademics and employers are concerned that students are not sufficiently prepared for college courses.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('please','a533fd527fdb7dd12a08541f6b71764e',NULL,'phrase','You use please in expressions such as as she pleases, whatever you please, and anything he pleases to indicate that someone can do or have whatever they want.','Women should be free to dress and act as they please.\nHe does whatever he pleases.',3,'/pliz/'),('arrogant','a638f85c84fd0bb99d95c7bb799ee043',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is arrogant behaves in a proud, unpleasant way toward other people because they believe that they are more important than others.','He was so arrogant.\nThat sounds arrogant, doesn\'t it?\nAt times the arrogance of those in power is quite blatant.',3,'/ærəgənt/'),('exhaust','a64c4d6c018a91f3de7cefed83dc4539',NULL,'uncount noun','Exhaust is the gas or steam that is produced when the engine of a vehicle is running.','...the exhaust from a car engine.\nThe city\'s streets are filthy and choked with exhaust fumes.',3,'/ɪgzɔst/'),('strain','a672e5c7a2f95d8fa96d819e080e77fb',NULL,'uncount noun','Strain is a state of worry and tension caused by a difficult situation.','She was tired and under great strain.',4,'/streɪn/'),('mean','a69106843e84e8963924b02d5231b346',NULL,'transitive verb','If one thing means another, the first thing leads to the second thing happening.','It would almost certainly mean the end of NATO.',5,'/min/'),('doleful','a6a0b5d6423dafcfe3f7ed6e35a21f9c',NULL,'adjective','A doleful expression, manner, or voice is depressing and miserable.','He gave me a long, doleful look.\n\"I don\'t know why they left,\" he said dolefully.',2,'/doʊlfəl/'),('concern','a71802185cf1303ee23cca1819db7766',NULL,'uncount noun','Concern is worry about a situation.','The group has expressed concern about reports of political violence in Africa.\nThe move follows growing public concern over the spread of the disease.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('pleasing','a87d140eaa1341e09e58ce9000c1a504',NULL,'adjective','Something that is pleasing gives you pleasure and satisfaction.','This area of France has a pleasing climate in August.\nSuch a view is pleasing.\nThe interior design is pleasingly simple.',3,'/plizɪŋ/'),('fluster','a87ff1029abb5e0e2cc8961516bbe308',NULL,'transitive verb','If you fluster someone, you make them feel nervous and confused by rushing them and preventing them from concentrating on what they are doing.','The General refused to be flustered.\nShe was so flustered that she forgot her reply.',1,'/flʌstər/'),('upset','a89651002473f628a0ecaf48b119dce9',NULL,'transitive verb','If you upset an object, you accidentally knock or push it over so that it scatters over a large area.','Don\'t upset the piles of sheets under the box.',4,'/ʌpsɛt/ /ʌpsɛt/'),('touchy','a8f96144ac37708bef0a687dbfb58823',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone as touchy, you mean that they are easily upset, offended, or irritated.','She is very touchy about her past.',2,'/tʌtʃi/'),('relieve','a8fd83e5aab70335815a0eba04a5f7ce',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something relieves you of an unpleasant feeling or difficult task, they take it from you.','A part-time bookkeeper will relieve you of the burden of chasing unpaid invoices.',0,'/rɪliv/'),('flat','a90b9e2546d37f9fb968cc33863f9040',NULL,'phrase','If you do something flat out, you do it as fast or as hard as you can.','Everyone is working flat out to try to trap those responsible.\n...a flat-out sprint.',3,'/flæt/'),('dread','aa0bee64b36608644088d911b279eade',NULL,'phrase','If you say that you dread to think what might happen, you mean that you are anxious about it because it is likely to be very unpleasant.','I dread to think what will happen in the case of a major emergency.',3,'/drɛd/'),('marvelous','aa38f9f5636c6461684c4d5537a40b93',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone or something as marvelous, you are emphasizing that they are very good.','It\'s the most marvelous piece of music.\nWe want people to think he\'s doing marvelously.',3,'/mɑrvələs/'),('dejected','aa6ed3ced24b9a23565d8ce5c3d764c4',NULL,'adjective','If you are dejected, you feel miserable or unhappy, especially because you have just been disappointed by something.','Everyone has days when they feel dejected or down.\nPassengers lined up dejectedly for the increasingly dirty toilets.',2,'/dɪdʒɛktɪd/'),('tremor','aa7a46ce1e0e334d67e49811d7964f77',NULL,'countable noun','If an event causes a tremor in a group or organisation, it threatens to make the group or organisation less strong or stable.','News of 160 lay-offs had sent tremors through the community.',3,'/trɛmər/'),('long','aae43ecb1315f30ad76472d56e4c3624',NULL,'adjective','If you describe a period of time or work as long, you mean it lasts for more hours or days than is usual, or seems to last for more time than it actually does.','Go to sleep. I\'ve got a long day tomorrow.\nShe was a TV reporter and worked long hours.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('rapture','ab37ae02d515fffd9d9e0cb6e59396cf',NULL,'uncount noun','Rapture is a feeling of extreme happiness or pleasure.','The film was shown to gasps of rapture at the Democratic Convention.\nHis speech was received with rapture by his supporters.',2,'/ræptʃər/'),('fanatic','ab39327bc0175e2fc87156dcfcc1e21b',NULL,'countable noun','If you say that someone is a fanatic, you mean that they are very enthusiastic about a particular activity, sport, or way of life.','Both Rod and Phil are football fanatics.',2,'/fənætɪk/'),('blessed','ab84ef0ed681a0a8819bad2b8e3e0b83',NULL,'adjective','If someone is blessed with a particular good quality or skill, they have that good quality or skill.','Both are blessed with an uncommon ability to fix things.',3,'/blɛst/ /blɛsɪd/'),('court','abae2dfa46343888192660a1d7831975',NULL,'phrase','If a legal matter is decided or settled out of court, it is decided without legal action being taken in a court of law.','The Government is anxious to keep the whole case out of court.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('horror','abda8ddeee98a89b194a1f13bf1d7b26',NULL,'countable noun','You can refer to extremely unpleasant or frightening experiences as horrors.','Can you possibly imagine all the horrors we have undergone since I last wrote you?',4,'/hɔrər/'),('content','acc76754c91e4839595b3872bec67ee1',NULL,'uncount noun','If you refer to the content or contents of something such as a book, television program, or website, you are referring to the subject that it deals with, the story that it tells, or the ideas that it expresses.','She is reluctant to discuss the content of the play.\nStricter controls were placed on the content of videos.',5,'/kɒntɛnt/'),('tremor','ad04dd92002a10ca4d39702c2b0364b5',NULL,'countable noun','A tremor is a shaking of your body or voice that you cannot control.','The old man has a tremor in his hands.',3,'/trɛmər/'),('mean','ad49709023fddcccf838509973a562ce',NULL,'adjective','If someone is being mean, they are being unkind to another person, for example by not allowing them to do something.','The little girls had locked themselves in the room because Mack had been mean to them.',5,'/min/'),('doubt','ad60770da3d7476d2a2bae7ae8a4efe6',NULL,'phrase','You use no doubt to indicate that you accept the truth of a particular point, but that you do not think it is important or contradicts the rest of what you are saying.','No doubt many will regard these as harsh words, but regrettably they are true.',4,'/daʊt/'),('cherish','ad6776b829508e17821d2b0125dfef23',NULL,'transitive verb','If you cherish a right, a privilege, or a principle, you regard it as important and try hard to keep it.','Chinese people cherish their independence and sovereignty.\nFreud called into question some deeply cherished beliefs.',3,'/tʃɛrɪʃ/'),('stun','ad8423c938f7c01ca6edd080679e3ad2',NULL,'transitive verb','If you are stunned by something, you are extremely shocked or surprised by it and are therefore unable to speak or do anything.','He\'s stunned by today\'s resignation of his longtime ally.\nWhen they told me she was missing I was totally stunned.',2,'/stʌn/'),('scare','adc50029b41099227e288562b0cdb5ca',NULL,'countable noun','A bomb scare or a security scare is a situation in which there is believed to be a bomb in a place.','Despite many recent bomb scares, no one has yet been hurt.',3,'/skɛər/'),('impetuous','aec50545f364224152f8a23ee22f4c75',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone as impetuous, you mean that they are likely to act quickly and suddenly without thinking or being careful.','He was young and impetuous.',2,'/ɪmpɛtʃuəs/'),('rage','aefb15a92e491cb7ce10dc32b87a99d2',NULL,'uncount noun','You can refer to the strong anger that someone feels in a particular situation as a particular rage, especially when this results in violent or aggressive behavior.','Cabin crews are reporting up to nine cases of air rage a week.',4,'/reɪdʒ/'),('fishy','af5788ca4238f946ba5eddf7c73bbc4f',NULL,'adjective','A fishy taste or smell reminds you of fish.','',2,'/fɪʃi/'),('incredible','af8ca9f12fb4c1c8071c7eccb116fc3c',NULL,'adjective','You use incredible to emphasize the degree, amount, or intensity of something.','I work an incredible amount of hours.\nIt was incredibly hard work.',3,'/ɪnkrɛdɪbəl/'),('forlorn','af9da7a0a27de7fcf9c41e1e148b561c',NULL,'adjective','A forlorn hope or attempt is one that you think has no chance of success.','Peasants have left the land in the forlorn hope of finding a better life in cities.',3,'/fɔrlɔrn/'),('provoke','b007ac55ecc0364cd69f005ba0f9fe02',NULL,'transitive verb','If you provoke someone, you deliberately annoy them and try to make them behave aggressively.','He started beating me when I was about fifteen but I didn\'t do anything to provoke him.',3,'/prəvoʊk/'),('grim','b03fe9c2f5eb6df64cb0dd7f3b0b6594',NULL,'adjective','A place that is grim is unattractive and depressing in appearance.','The city might be grim at first, but there is a vibrancy and excitement.',3,'/grɪm/'),('horror','b0a66396f415996aaf9c1d7a41b1f899',NULL,'adjective','You can refer to an account of a very unpleasant experience or event as a horror story.','...a horror story about lost luggage while flying.',4,'/hɔrər/'),('emotional','b0a923a3442a1cf99f2f28d5e24b46fc',NULL,'adjective','If someone is or becomes emotional, they show their feelings very openly, especially because they are upset.','He is a very emotional man.',4,'/ɪmoʊʃənəl/'),('downhearted','b1a5953c69ce0f87f635b28ffb4b69db',NULL,'adjective','If you are downhearted, you are feeling sad and discouraged.','Max sighed, sounding even more downhearted.',1,'/daʊnhɑrtɪd/'),('energetic','b1e751b32fbbf6e7dc64496bcdd99a92',NULL,'adjective','An energetic person is very active and does not feel at all tired. An energetic activity involves a lot of physical movement and power.','Ten year-olds are incredibly energetic.\nDavid chewed energetically on the gristly steak.',3,'/ɛnərdʒɛtɪk/'),('radically','b1e8a3a0ec7e56885dd390b42f8eaa65','radical',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),('strike','b207500f2dacedca211433349e86a5c9',NULL,'transitive verb','If you strike a balance, you do something that is halfway between two extremes.','At times like that you have to strike a balance between sleep and homework.',4,'/straɪk/'),('outrage','b300c53ce333d534758de59f6f08c3f3',NULL,'countable noun','You can refer to an act or event that angers and shocks you as an outrage.','The latest outrage was to have been a coordinated gun and bomb attack on the station.',3,'/aʊtreɪdʒ/ /aʊtreɪdʒ/'),('flat','b392f24686718bea5ba2eb364f741fcc',NULL,'adjective','A flat denial or refusal is definite and firm, and is unlikely to be changed.','The Foreign Ministry has issued a flat denial of any involvement.\nHe flatly refused to discuss it.',3,'/flæt/'),('flat','b3cf44f18e74a96ef3acde5fe1bc0466',NULL,'adjective','Something that is flat is level, smooth, or even, rather than sloping, curved, or uneven.','Tiles can be fixed to any surface as long as it\'s flat, firm and dry.\n...windows which a thief can reach from a drainpipe or flat roof.',3,'/flæt/'),('touch','b3f3361ab802f13769c29a1bfe1ff70d',NULL,'quantifier','A touch of something is a very small amount of it.','She thought she just had a touch of the flu.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('mean','b42a193e6719a4e792d3492c48a2aa36',NULL,'transitive verb','If something means something to you, it is important to you in some way.','The idea that she witnessed this shameful incident meant nothing to him.',5,'/min/'),('positive','b48a610e6ef8f46647581f949b748f80',NULL,'adjective','A positive fact, situation, or experience is pleasant and helpful to you in some way.','The parting from his sister had a positive effect on John.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('detest','b4d364139cbfcc2e0e4d9f9a7b77f319',NULL,'transitive verb','If you detest someone or something, you dislike them very much.','My mother detested him.',2,'/dɪtɛst/'),('exhaust','b586624be6759e8ab532aa741235269a',NULL,'transitive verb','If you have exhausted a subject or topic, you have talked about it so much that there is nothing more to say about it.','She and Chantal must have exhausted the subject of clothes.',3,'/ɪgzɔst/'),('touch','b5a319e164653318e83406f5b0f21161',NULL,'transitive verb','If something that someone says or does touches you, it affects you emotionally, often because you see that they are suffering a lot or that they are being very kind.','It has touched me deeply to see how these people live.\nI was touched to find that he regards me as engaging.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('devoted','b5ba7b0d4ea9c7fd9b4f79bd07e64808',NULL,'adjective','Something that is devoted to a particular thing deals only with that thing or contains only that thing.','A large part of the Internet is now devoted to weblogs.',4,'/dɪvoʊtɪd/'),('court','b62c7fd220f1a4b533631e0a85aa4335',NULL,'countable noun','You can refer to the people in a court, especially the judge, jury, or magistrates, as a court.','A court at Tampa, Florida has convicted five officials on charges of handling millions of dollars earned from illegal drug deals.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('crazy','b6adf4d2e8123c9460608c9fdff0f3de',NULL,'adjective','If you are crazy about someone, you are deeply in love with them.','We\'re crazy about each other.',4,'/kreɪzi/'),('sensuous','b8573273d5446144f71e7ff96608ad63',NULL,'adjective','Something that is sensuous gives pleasure to the mind or body through the senses.','The film is ravishing to look at and boasts a sensuous musical score.\nShe lay in the deep bath for a long time, enjoying its sensuously perfumed water.',3,'/sɛnʃuəs/'),('panic','b898390f0ed8d9eebf8ceb745ac1872c',NULL,'variable noun','Panic is a very strong feeling of anxiety or fear that makes you act without thinking carefully.','An earthquake has hit the capital, causing damage to buildings and panic among the population.',4,'/pænɪk/'),('hesitate','b8ad3522e3537c3e12154606dc660723',NULL,'transitive verb','You can use hesitate in expressions such as \"don\'t hesitate to call me\" or \"don\'t hesitate to contact us\" when you are telling someone that they should do something as soon as it needs to be done and should not worry about disturbing other people.','In the event of difficulties, please do not hesitate to contact our Customer Service Department.',3,'/hɛzɪteɪt/'),('fright','b91132a053517549db7432807739a6ee',NULL,'countable noun','A fright is an experience which makes you suddenly afraid.','The snake picked up its head and stuck out its tongue which gave everyone a fright.',3,'/fraɪt/'),('strain','b9487bd5881e078ac5f28f8c85332fe0',NULL,'uncount noun','Strain is a force that pushes, pulls, or stretches something in a way that may damage it.','Place your hands under your buttocks to take some of the strain off your back.',4,'/streɪn/'),('beat','b95ac760336c8e9c509a4e0f320442d6',NULL,'transitive verb','To beat a time limit or an event means to achieve something before that time or event.','They were trying to beat the midnight deadline.',4,'/bit/'),('suspicious','b9cc7f1c16847e99bb90b5c2c1b9ca58',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone or something as suspicious, you mean that there is some aspect of them which makes you think that they are involved in a crime or a dishonest activity.','He reported that two suspicious-looking characters had approached Callendar.\nThey\'ll question them as to whether anyone was seen acting suspiciously in the area over the last few days.',4,'/səspɪʃəs/'),('try','ba33335940f3a9a517c672342489229b',NULL,'countable noun','In the game of rugby, a try is the action of scoring by putting the ball down behind the goal line of the opposing team.','The French, who led 21-3 at half time, scored eight tries.',5,'/traɪ/'),('beat','ba4fbfd9f0ec0214be880c88d13d5eb7',NULL,'transitive verb','If an attack or an attempt is beaten off or is beaten back, it is stopped, often temporarily.','The rescuers were beaten back by strong winds and currents.',4,'/bit/'),('flat','ba5a4b105aa4b95a4d56218535a80ed6',NULL,'adverb','If someone sings flat or if a musical instrument is flat, their singing or the instrument is slightly lower in pitch than it should be.','She had a tendency to sing flat.',3,'/flæt/'),('satiate','ba801933c2d059a0b9a106a42b6f6979',NULL,'transitive verb','If something such as food or pleasure satiates you, you have all that you need or all that you want of it, often so much that you become tired of it.','The dinner was enough to satiate the gourmets.',1,'/seɪʃieɪt/'),('touching','bb2aa175b0d401962842e3f5f1977980',NULL,'adjective','If something is touching, it causes feelings of sadness or sympathy.','Her story is the touching tale of a wife who stood by the husband she loved.',4,'/tʌtʃɪŋ/'),('desirable','bb93ddc6f9a4522572ec1404e6e8d6e3',NULL,'adjective','Someone who is desirable is considered to be sexually attractive.','...the young women of his own age whom his classmates thought most desirable.\nHe had not at all overrated Veronica\'s desirability.',4,'/dɪzaɪərəbəl/'),('realize','bbd3b5cf8118ad3d90930ff3a775f27e',NULL,'transitive verb','If something realizes a particular amount of money when it is sold, that amount of money is paid for it.','A selection of correspondence from P.G. Wodehouse realized 2,000 dollars.\n...a total cash realization of about $23 million.',4,'/riəlaɪz/'),('strike','bbee5ac6e8ff093dc73987d36bc54866',NULL,'transitive verb','If an idea or thought strikes you, it suddenly comes into your mind.','A thought struck her. Was she jealous of her mother, then?',4,'/straɪk/'),('beat','bbeeccccfe9f73514dfd65d695e4f100',NULL,'countable noun','The beat of a piece of music is the main rhythm that it has.','...the thumping beat of rock music.',4,'/bit/'),('motivation','bc2232a37b35a7a1f8e58b2deb03deb0',NULL,'countable noun','Your motivation for doing something is what causes you to want to do it.','Money is my motivation.',0,'/moʊtɪveɪʃən/'),('content','bdc99ea27ee79c19bc86f9c3d8c65025',NULL,'uncount noun','The content of something such as an educational course or a program of action is the elements that it consists of.','Previous students have had nothing but praise for the course content and staff.',5,'/kɒntɛnt/'),('indefatigable','bde1fa841ac23480fd27cbc3e5eba2de',NULL,'adjective','You use indefatigable to describe someone who never gets tired of doing something.','His indefatigable spirit helped him to cope with his illness.\nShe worked indefatigably to interest children in music.',2,'/ɪndɪfætɪgəbəl/'),('strike','be5f69926bf1483c7db9470c3ae3fce2',NULL,'transitive verb','If you strike one thing against another, or if one thing strikes against another, the first thing hits the second thing.','Wilde fell and struck his head on the stone floor.',4,'/straɪk/'),('loathe','bf16ff6215a1f928acb47b7350ebe64d',NULL,'transitive verb','If you loathe something or someone, you dislike them very much.','The two men loathe each other.',2,'/loʊð/'),('touch','bf9d9b553431e9750547f46bc7d4c250',NULL,'reciprocal verb','If two things are touching, or if one thing touches another, or if you touch two things, their surfaces come into contact with each other.','Their knees were touching.\nA cyclist crashed when he touched wheels with another rider.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('touch','c0e713e189829fdeb232b6cec144a475',NULL,'phrase','If you get in touch with someone, you contact them by writing to them or telephoning them. If you are, keep, or stay in touch with them, you write, phone, or visit each other regularly.','I will get in touch with my lawyer about this.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('vigorous','c1281e9a2a0e70ce6dff6654bee2fbcd',NULL,'adjective','Vigorous physical activities involve using a lot of energy, usually to do short and repeated actions.','Very vigorous exercise can increase the risk of heart attacks.\nHe shook his head vigorously.',3,'/vɪgərəs/'),('sentimental','c148a496fc093b684ad26466fca88521',NULL,'adjective','Sentimental means relating to or involving feelings such as pity or love, especially for things in the past.','Our paintings and photographs are of sentimental value only.',3,'/sɛntɪmɛntəl/'),('urge','c149e4d8e808ccf3dea552d4739cca66',NULL,'transitive verb','If you urge a course of action, you strongly advise that it should be taken.','He urged restraint on the security forces.',4,'/ɜrdʒ/'),('beat','c1b3e31af1ebb08551bb2f61b9aff7d1',NULL,'intransitive verb','When your heart or pulse beats, it continually makes regular rhythmic movements.','I felt my heart beating faster.',4,'/bit/'),('gloomy','c22057f906274cac847061c44a0cc85b',NULL,'adjective','If a situation is gloomy, it does not give you much hope of success or happiness.','...a gloomy picture of an economy sliding into recession.\nOfficials say the outlook for next year is gloomy.',3,'/glumi/'),('urge','c2ba3c3af062cf51181caac2dd420e94',NULL,'countable noun','If you have an urge to do or have something, you have a strong wish to do or have it.','He had an urge to open a shop of his own.',4,'/ɜrdʒ/'),('curio