ns another, it shows that the second thing exists or is true.','An enlarged prostate does not necessarily mean cancer.',5,'/min/'),('flat','d038a2bcf428de68f4057fc71bed363c',NULL,'adjective','Flat means horizontal and not upright.','Two men near him threw themselves flat.',3,'/flæt/'),('touch','d1e25bfeb96304165f35d2e9fa9a73f2',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you touch on a particular subject or problem, you mention it or write briefly about it.','The film touches on these issues, but only superficially.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('court','d215663394461f035c30d4da5ef993e3',NULL,'transitive verb','To court a particular person, group, or country means to try to please them or improve your relations with them, often so that they will do something that you want them to do.','Both Democratic and Republican parties are courting former supporters of Ross Perot.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('positive','d35bc42da6d28022cb0849838dc24959',NULL,'adjective','A positive response to something indicates agreement, approval, or encouragement.','There\'s been a positive response to the U.N. Secretary-General\'s recent peace efforts.\nHe responded positively and accepted the fee of $1,000 I had offered.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('relieve','d3df6f75b3832bf1de5ddf1b3f86051e',NULL,'transitive verb','If you relieve someone, you take their place and continue to do the job or duty that they have been doing.','At seven o\'clock the night nurse came in to relieve her.',0,'/rɪliv/'),('mean','d407475d0ccb14f29e25248b42f46fdd',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that something was meant to happen, you believe that it was made to happen by God or fate, and did not just happen by chance.','John was constantly reassuring me that we were meant to be together.',5,'/min/'),('suspect','d436e6169e0b72ea02db59205461d122',NULL,'transitive verb','If you suspect that something dishonest or unpleasant has been done, you believe that it has probably been done. If you suspect someone of doing an action of this kind, you believe that they probably did it.','He suspected that the woman staying in the flat above was using heroin.\nIt was perfectly all right, he said, because the police had not suspected him of anything.',4,'/səspɛkt/ /sʌspɛkt/'),('mean','d437ae6884ac84be9e49c251c9f09782',NULL,'phrase','You say \"I mean\" when making clearer something that you have just said.','It was his idea. Gordon\'s, I mean.',5,'/min/'),('mean','d438106079e5924487617af6a01ab97f',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that someone meant to do something, you are saying that they did it deliberately.','I didn\'t mean to hurt you.\nIf that sounds harsh, it is meant to.',5,'/min/'),('exhaust','d5727e39501f1c022d02ee6cab45976e',NULL,'transitive verb','If you exhaust something such as money or food, you use or finish it all.','We have exhausted all our material resources.',3,'/ɪgzɔst/'),('upset','d59ebf29adddc46a79b8da034631578d',NULL,'adjective','If you are upset, you are unhappy or disappointed because something bad has happened to you.','After she died I felt very, very upset.\nMarta looked upset.',4,'/ʌpsɛt/ /ʌpsɛt/'),('presumptuous','d74e8b132f7cc42a92c7585566000b5c',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone or their behavior as presumptuous, you disapprove of them because they are doing something that they have no right or authority to do.','It would be presumptuous to judge what the outcome will be.',2,'/prɪzʌmptʃuəs/'),('indignant','d768789ae13605260de5626c16d3880f',NULL,'adjective','If you are indignant, you are shocked and angry, because you think that something is unjust or unfair.','He is indignant at suggestions that they were secret agents.\nHe was indignant that his rival was offered the job.\n\"That is not true,\" Erica said indignantly.',3,'/ɪndɪgnənt/'),('faint','d769612f8ed3cf48575a697c7d87df1e',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you faint, you lose consciousness for a short time, especially because you are hungry, or because of pain, heat, or shock.','She suddenly fell forward on to the table and fainted.',3,'/feɪnt/'),('fret','d77758a806d31554a6eb775d00758a08',NULL,'countable noun','The frets on a musical instrument such as a guitar are the raised lines across its neck.','',2,'/frɛt/'),('long','d815f78a09445b0225a407d9dfe59d67',NULL,'phrase','Something that is no longer the case used to be the case but is not the case now. You can also say that something is not the case any longer.','Food shortages are no longer a problem.\nShe could no longer afford to keep him at school.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('enthusiasm','d85c246ec77a9e23561fce9809634609',NULL,'variable noun','Enthusiasm is great eagerness to be involved in a particular activity that you like and enjoy or that you think is important.','Their skill and enthusiasm has gotten them on the team.',4,'/ɪnθuziæzəm/'),('try','d8693bb85839934f53989b9ea050fc53',NULL,'transitive verb','If you try something new or different, you use it, do it, or experience it in order to discover its qualities or effects.','It\'s best not to try a new recipe for the first time on such an important occasion.',5,'/traɪ/'),('mean','d8c66b9f1b78368688bbbdb31476dd3c',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone as mean, you are being critical of them because they are unwilling to spend much money or to use very much of a particular thing.','',5,'/min/'),('content','d90c0db081971ef2833bb5db4540f928',NULL,'adjective','If you are content, you are fairly happy or satisfied.','He says his daughter is quite content.',5,'/kəntɛnt/'),('touch','d914bd3706a4e2f5588f393bd4e14cfa',NULL,'transitive verb','If something has not been touched, nobody has dealt with it or taken care of it.','When John began to restore the house in the 1960s, nothing had been touched for 40 years.',4,'/tʌtʃ/'),('scare','d9a01184444de3887069668f7530a5bf',NULL,'transitive verb','If something scares you, it frightens or worries you.','You\'re scaring me.\nThe prospect of failure scares me rigid.',3,'/skɛər/'),('menace','d9b196ebf5f6b0d28d85d177742c6b21',NULL,'transitive verb','If you say that one thing menaces another, you mean that the first thing is likely to cause the second thing serious harm.','They seem determined to menace the United States and its allies.',3,'/mɛnɪs/'),('incredulity','d9f2db351d5462301a8f5dfff745e88f',NULL,'uncount noun','If someone reacts with incredulity to something, they are unable to believe it because it is very surprising or shocking.','The announcement has been met with incredulity.',2,'/ɪnkrɪdulɪti/'),('fright','d9f36e50e3dd747df5a4ade5e17ca342',NULL,'uncount noun','Fright is a sudden feeling of fear, especially the fear that you feel when something unpleasant surprises you.','The steam pipes rattled suddenly, and Franklin jumped with fright.\nThe birds smashed into the top of their cages in fright.',3,'/fraɪt/'),('startle','dacbbb5b66e013b5c59731891b1901b0',NULL,'transitive verb','If something sudden and unexpected startles you, it surprises and frightens you slightly.','The telephone startled him.\nMartha gave her a startled look.',2,'/stɑrtəl/'),('beat','de0e8ebf8f8166aa761d579be1da4c10',NULL,'transitive verb','If you beat someone or something, you hit them very hard.','My wife tried to stop them and they beat her.',4,'/bit/'),('flat','de57db7fe6d054cade551147657df7da',NULL,'adjective','A flat rate, price, or percentage is one that is fixed and which applies in every situation.','Fees are charged at a flat rate, rather than on a percentage basis.',3,'/flæt/'),('mean','df62c5ca44f210bde9d1cc02051e44d5',NULL,'phrase','If a name, word, or phrase means something to you, you have heard it before and you know what it refers to.','\"Oh, Gairdner,\" he said, as if that meant something to him.',5,'/min/'),('desperate','e01e3f5d10aaff7ca90bf96e5732cd59',NULL,'adjective','If you are desperate, you are in such a bad situation that you are willing to try anything to change it.','Troops are needed to help get food into Kosovo where people are in desperate need.\nThousands are desperately trying to leave their battered homes and villages.',4,'/dɛspərɪt/'),('miserable','e0d86a7ca708caaffbadafa6521f52b0',NULL,'adjective','You can describe a quantity or quality as miserable when you think that it is much smaller or worse than it ought to be.','Our speed over the ground was a miserable 2.2 knots.\n...the miserably inadequate supply of books now provided for schools.',3,'/mɪzərəbəl/'),('concern','e130e5829293b2e809ac7e7dbab37ced',NULL,'transitive verb','If you concern yourself with something, you give it attention because you think that it is important.','I didn\'t concern myself with politics.\nThe agency is more concerned with making arty ads than understanding its clients\' businesses.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('devote','e167006aad4f71889e84fa8af79efef8',NULL,'transitive verb','If you devote a particular proportion of a piece of writing or a speech to a particular subject, you deal with the subject in that amount of space or time.','He devoted a major section of his massive report to an analysis of U.S. aircraft design.',4,'/dɪvoʊt/'),('positive','e1756f841306a2ac1073fe952e19029d',NULL,'adjective','If you make a positive decision or take positive action, you do something definite in order to deal with a task or problem.','There are positive changes that should be implemented in the rearing of animals.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('rage','e1a45c7754382c11f8d094e59a50a1d5',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you rage about something, you speak or think very angrily about it.','Monroe was on the phone, raging about her mistreatment by the brothers.\nInside, Frannie was raging.',4,'/reɪdʒ/'),('malicious','e2333f1ea2dfcd6f563bfa3bed56d44d',NULL,'adjective','If you describe someone\'s words or actions as malicious, you mean that they are intended to harm people or their reputation, or cause them embarrassment and upset.','That might merely have been malicious gossip.\n...his maliciously accurate imitation of Hubert de Burgh.',3,'/məlɪʃəs/'),('beat','e292a7e9116b0f80a1855675a7c3ea23',NULL,'phrase','If you intend to do something but someone beats you to it, they do it before you do.','Don\'t be too long about it or you\'ll find someone has beaten you to it.',4,'/bit/'),('horror','e35b8f66fa6f569311c942e58d0e62b6',NULL,'uncount noun','Horror is a feeling of great shock, fear, and worry caused by something extremely unpleasant.','I felt numb with horror.',4,'/hɔrər/'),('strike','e3613e9a150354501f996bc3224a20a9',NULL,'intransitive verb','When workers strike, they go on strike.','...their recognition of the workers\' right to strike.\nThey shouldn\'t be striking for more money.\nThe strikers want higher wages, which state governments say they can\'t afford.',4,'/straɪk/'),('chafe','e383f5d2f7b727638548e8a8cdd05aa2',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you chafe at something such as a restriction, you feel annoyed about it.','He had chafed at having to take orders from another.\nHe was chafing under the company\'s new ownership.',2,'/tʃeɪf/'),('strain','e48a5b3b6f50c4990e17016282da0be9',NULL,'transitive verb','To strain something means to make it do more than it is able to do.','The volume of scheduled flights is straining the air traffic control system.',4,'/streɪn/'),('mania','e4959ef93fe78f1e028eda15f35d201d',NULL,'countable noun','If you say that a person or group has a mania for something, you mean that they enjoy it very much or spend a lot of time on it.','The mania for dinosaurs began in the late 1800s.',3,'/meɪniə/'),('doubt','e4b528176a69a8d9da8fb447f2f32b75',NULL,'transitive verb','If you doubt someone or doubt their word, you think that they may not be telling the truth.','No one directly involved with the case doubted him.',4,'/daʊt/'),('strain','e4e17ebad0285234f23cc241091efe75',NULL,'variable noun','Strain is an injury to a muscle in your body, caused by using the muscle too much or twisting it.','Avoid muscle strain by warming up with slow jogging.',4,'/streɪn/'),('depression','e4e1dc60ab3ca1434a851653418b416f',NULL,'countable noun','A depression is a time when there is very little economic activity, which causes a lot of unemployment and poverty.','He never forgot the hardships he witnessed during the Great Depression of the 1930s.',4,'/dɪprɛʃən/'),('mean','e4e3f1ad947f1360de0e88d9e2b30670',NULL,'transitive verb','If doing one thing means doing another, it involves doing the second thing.','Children universally prefer to live in peace and security, even if that means living with only one parent.',5,'/min/'),('concern','e6025b7d2d8c627e06415b67a6052f03',NULL,'countable noun','You can refer to a company or business as a concern, usually when you are describing what type of company or business it is.','If not a large concern, the Potomac Nursery was at least a successful one.',5,'/kənsɜrn/'),('mean','e621712741e7d6ddd19146db6cf2aabb',NULL,'transitive verb','If you want to know what a word, code, signal, or gesture means, you want to know what it refers to or what its message is.','\"Credible\" means \"believable.\"\nWhat does \"evidence\" mean?',5,'/min/'),('please','e6d6e82b399263bb40867a37fcbcbc35',NULL,'convention','You can say please in order to attract someone\'s attention politely.','Please, Miss Smith, a moment.',3,'/pliz/'),('content','e7bdcda73b493d9d3eff6a08bc88085d',NULL,'adjective','If you are content with something, you are willing to accept it, rather than wanting something more or something better.','I am content to admire the mountains from below.\nI\'m perfectly content with the way the campaign has gone.',5,'/kəntɛnt/'),('affectionate','e7cf47e280007772db3c515d926d1be4',NULL,'adjective','If you are affectionate, you show your love or fondness for another person in the way that you behave toward them.','They seemed devoted to each other and were openly affectionate.\nHe looked affectionately at his niece.',3,'/əfɛkʃənɪt/'),('emotional','e83a8b67de8b3908b5a2daccee0fa1c6',NULL,'adjective','An emotional situation or issue is one that causes people to have strong feelings.','Abortion is a very emotional issue.\nIn an emotionally charged speech, he said he was resigning.',4,'/ɪmoʊʃənəl/'),('impulse','e8f251a2c87c1b74561bd410dcfd8a38',NULL,'phrase','If you do something on impulse, you suddenly decide to do it, without planning it.','Sean\'s a fast thinker, and he acts on impulse.',4,'/ɪmpʌls/'),('realize','e90d6cddd3a515f9584b20de8958dbcc',NULL,'transitive verb','If you realize that something is true, you become aware of that fact or understand it.','As soon as we realized something was wrong, we moved the children away.\nPeople don\'t realize how serious this recession has actually been.\nThere is now a growing realization that things cannot go on like this for much longer.',4,'/riəlaɪz/'),('skeptical','e9bbcd523685e1c9471034481bf9b9ed',NULL,'adjective','If you are skeptical about something, you have doubts about it.','Others here are more skeptical about the chances for justice being done.',3,'/skɛptɪkəl/'),('radical','ea785cef9857ebcbae63bcd9f8de05e9',NULL,'adjective','A radical is someone who has radical views.','Vanessa and I had been student radicals together at Berkeley from 1965 to 1967.',4,'/rædɪkəl/'),('flat','eadb6c3033fb46a42e755c38f8df10f5',NULL,'adjective','A flat tire, ball, or balloon does not have enough air in it.','One vehicle with a flat tire can bring the highway to a standstill.',3,'/flæt/'),('positive','ebd7405e0b7e8541b16867c2e987f674',NULL,'adjective','The positive in a situation is the good and pleasant aspects of it.','He prefers to focus on the positive.',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('zest','ec1c149b5356c51bc207cbfb877ecb57',NULL,'uncount noun','Zest is a quality in an activity or situation which you find exciting.','Live interviews add zest and a touch of the unexpected to any piece of research.',2,'/zɛst/'),('sick','ec67f1f8527778bdd77fb7c8ca183205',NULL,'adjective','If you are sick, the food that you have eaten comes up from your stomach and out of your mouth. If you feel sick, you feel as if you are going to be sick.','She got up and was sick in the sink.\nThe very thought of food made him feel sick.',4,'/sɪk/'),('complaint','ecbd7f1b7ca802ba1d9e97f2588dbdd1',NULL,'countable noun','A complaint is a reason for complaining.','My main complaint is that we can\'t go out on the racecourse anymore.',4,'/kəmpleɪnt/'),('terror','eccb902f40f2d9906147dde306815dd7',NULL,'countable noun','A terror is something that makes you very frightened.','As a boy, he had a real terror of facing people.',4,'/tɛrər/'),('astonished','edc13fbf09c7d22047216d524aacc9a3',NULL,'adjective','If you are astonished by something, you are very surprised about it.','They were astonished to find the driver was a six-year-old boy.',0,'/əstɒnɪʃt/'),('gloomy','ede82d592274feb654730437ab258c1e',NULL,'adjective','If a place is gloomy, it is almost dark so that you cannot see very well.','Inside it\'s gloomy after all that sunshine.',3,'/glumi/'),('tremor','edf70f92b0f58159fb58cc60525be748',NULL,'countable noun','A tremor is a small earthquake.','The earthquake sent tremors through the region.',3,'/trɛmər/'),('emotional','edfeb9784553663918f9d2bac06fe109',NULL,'adjective','Emotional means concerned with emotions and feelings.','I needed this man\'s love, and the emotional support he was giving me.\nAre you saying that you\'re becoming emotionally involved with me?',4,'/ɪmoʊʃənəl/'),('try','ee14186e86729a61414369916634d296',NULL,'transitive verb','If you try a particular place or person, you go to that place or person because you think that they may be able to provide you with what you want.','Have you tried the local music shops?',5,'/traɪ/'),('miserable','eefa0a214549d2e8204e6741cf62db6b',NULL,'adjective','If you describe a place or situation as miserable, you mean that it makes you feel unhappy or depressed.','There was nothing at all in this miserable place to distract him.',3,'/mɪzərəbəl/'),('ardor','efff6f64149c7b0c63732db8fd24951d',NULL,'uncount noun','Ardor is a strong, intense feeling of love or enthusiasm for someone or something.','...songs of genuine passion and ardor.',2,'/ɑrdər/'),('passionate','f057a346b63a6eba44c1008a6d765e76',NULL,'adjective','A passionate person has very strong feelings about something or a strong belief in something.','...his passionate commitment to peace.\nHe is very passionate about the project.\nI am passionately opposed to the death penalty.',3,'/pæʃənɪt/'),('hail','f0ef5b5a26a16cc02bb709ccf5f67388',NULL,'singular noun','A hail of things, usually small objects, is a large number of them that hit you at the same time and with great force.','The victim was hit by a hail of bullets.',3,'/heɪl/'),('preference','f0fb576bd7b6dfc1848730a2df8f2660',NULL,'uncount noun','If you give preference to someone with a particular qualification or feature, you choose them rather than someone else.','The Pentagon has said it will give preference to companies with which it can do business electronically.',4,'/prɛfərəns/'),('gorge','f11530be47c22c7d1990880a5f594a91',NULL,'transitive verb','If you gorge on something or gorge yourself on it, you eat lots of it in a very greedy way.','I could spend each day gorging on chocolate.',2,'/gɔrdʒ/'),('court','f16f56c70da65cf24c59d24c803b60c9',NULL,'phrase','If you go to court or take someone to court, you take legal action against them.','They have received at least twenty thousand dollars each but went to court to demand more.',5,'/kɔrt/'),('suspicious','f1794fa826da82269c677208774ff5cd',NULL,'adjective','If you are suspicious of someone or something, you do not trust them, and are careful when dealing with them.','He was rightly suspicious of meeting me until I reassured him I was not writing about him.\n\"What is it you want me to do?\" Adams asked suspiciously.',4,'/səspɪʃəs/'),('grim','f185b21c0200e36eb2d9f88612f38078',NULL,'adjective','A situation or piece of information that is grim is unpleasant, depressing, and difficult to accept.','They painted a grim picture of growing crime.\nThere was further grim economic news yesterday.',3,'/grɪm/'),('doubt','f1a36ec319fc9e03d662d7e2eecd4ba2',NULL,'variable noun','If you have doubt or doubts about something, you feel uncertain about it and do not know whether it is true or possible. If you say you have no doubt about it, you mean that you are certain it is true.','This raises doubts about the point of advertising.\nThere is little doubt that man has had an impact on the Earth\'s climate.',4,'/daʊt/'),('brighten','f1eb348c0f8204d7626a964950b7ed2d',NULL,'intransitive verb','If the weather brightens, it becomes less cloudy or rainy, and the sun starts to shine.','By early afternoon the weather had brightened.',2,'/braɪtən/'),('dubious','f1fd23b8516198e1b383da657fe5c70d',NULL,'adjective','If you are dubious about something, you are not completely sure about it and have not yet made up your mind about it.','My parents were a bit dubious about it all at first but we soon convinced them.\nHe eyed Coyne dubiously.',3,'/dubiəs/'),('please','f25c165f303902bf533c7347df08e2fe',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something pleases you, they make you feel happy and satisfied.','More than anything, I want to please you.\nIt pleased him to talk to her.\nHe appeared anxious to please.',3,'/pliz/'),('bless','f31c26a64562301e98e96d4cae9931a3',NULL,'convention','You can say \"bless you\" to someone who has just sneezed.','',3,'/blɛs/'),('menace','f3be4500eb2bcb4df071082d20cf5166',NULL,'uncount noun','Menace is a quality or atmosphere that gives you the feeling that you are in danger or that someone wants to harm you.','There is a pervading sense of menace.',3,'/mɛnɪs/'),('passionate','f4274a4a3c721c68c7cadf3f711df1be',NULL,'adjective','A passionate person has strong romantic or sexual feelings and expresses them in their behavior.','...a beautiful, passionate woman of twenty-six.\nHe was passionately in love with her.',3,'/pæʃənɪt/'),('torment','f52a3da75bc2d3e037061078ac0765df',NULL,'countable noun','A torment is something that causes extreme suffering, usually mental suffering.','Sooner or later most writers end up making books about the torments of being a writer.',3,'/tɔrmɛnt/ /tɔrmɛnt/'),('tortuous','f62cc04f192dba934b915ccbd7405e24',NULL,'adjective','A tortuous road is full of bends and twists.','The only road access is a tortuous mountain route.',2,'/tɔrtʃuəs/'),('long','f6bc61b7d964bd33e1dc11ac13c5e5e1',NULL,'adjective','A long piece of clothing covers the whole of someone\'s legs or more of their legs than usual. Clothes with long sleeves cover the whole of someone\'s arms.','She is wearing a long black dress.',5,'/lɔŋ/'),('flounder','f6f61044eaee07155447c3fb71e86e12',NULL,'intransitive verb','If you say that someone is floundering, you are criticizing them for not making decisions or for not knowing what to say or do.','Right now, you\'ve got a president who\'s floundering, trying to find some way to get his campaign jump-started.',2,'/flaʊndər/'),('objective','f744fffb5575596ea2bd12ddb24f511a',NULL,'adjective','If someone is objective, they base their opinions on facts rather than on their personal feelings.','I believe that a journalist should be completely objective.\nTry to view situations more objectively, especially with regard to work.\nThe psychiatrist must learn to maintain an unusual degree of objectivity.',4,'/əbdʒɛktɪv/'),('positive','f74802c9e32a8f9d9f3bfafda643ccaa',NULL,'adjective','If something has a positive electrical charge, it has the same charge as a proton and the opposite charge to a neutron.','',5,'/pɒzɪtɪv/'),('distress','f78c9a3f2412a5ec1bd3b34ae0790765',NULL,'transitive verb','If someone or something distresses you, they cause you to be upset or worried.','The idea of Toni being in danger distresses him enormously.',3,'/dɪstrɛs/'),('bias','f7c352e3235da7396b5990decaf5ad4f',NULL,'transitive verb','To bias someone means to influence them in favor of a particular choice.','We mustn\'t allow it to bias our teaching.',4,'/baɪəs/'),('halt','f895dba47ac2f5779475c5a7f56aa3b0',NULL,'transitive verb','When something such as growth, development, or activity halts or when you halt it, it stops completely.','Striking workers halted production at the auto plant yesterday.',3,'/hɔlt/'),('gorge','f8b244bb782d4db6e116e87df5693a91',NULL,'countable noun','A gorge is a deep, narrow valley with very steep sides, usually where a river passes through mountains or an area of hard rock.','...the deep gorge between these hills.',2,'/gɔrdʒ/'),('strike','f9d88847811ee2e6a124a174ba749fe3',NULL,'transitive verb','When you strike a match, you make it produce a flame by moving it quickly against something rough.','Robina struck a match and held it to the crumpled newspaper in the grate.',4,'/straɪk/'),('sick','fa02c57069d955c3bf0fc320ea599906',NULL,'adjective','If you describe something such as a joke or story as sick, you mean that it deals with death or suffering in an unpleasantly humorous way.','...a sick joke about a cat.',4,'/sɪk/'),('flat','fa9ae8aea5666e6e8b363957e17356cc',NULL,'adjective','A flat battery has lost some or all of its electrical charge.','',3,'/flæt/'),('impatient','fa9cd761ab1379c5e3b1a2549f984b3e',NULL,'adjective','If you are impatient, you are easily irritated by things.','Beware of being too impatient with others.\n\"Come on, David,\" Harry said impatiently.\nThere was a hint of impatience in his tone.',3,'/ɪmpeɪʃənt/'),('strike','fb62ceec4e6cbdc71490358bd9d3e217',NULL,'transitive verb','If you strike words from a document or an official record, you remove them.','Strike that from the minutes.',4,'/straɪk/'),('distract','fb7d9f43faf07972c36c273458799ca3',NULL,'transitive verb','If something distracts you or your attention from something, it takes your attention away from it.','Tom admits that playing video games sometimes distracts him from his homework.\nDon\'t let yourself be distracted by fashionable theories.',3,'/dɪstrækt/'),('beat','fbac938f417d59d3258dc0552109e80d',NULL,'countable noun','A police officer\'s or journalist\'s beat is the area for which he or she is responsible.','A policeman was patrolling his regular beat, when he saw a group of boys milling about the street.',4,'/bit/'),('enrage','fbee56b45e3d8b3f7ad741ef215b6ee4',NULL,'transitive verb','If you are enraged by something, it makes you extremely angry.','Many were enraged by the discriminatory practice.',2,'/ɪnreɪdʒ/'),('horror','fc107863a32eb094addac5e59d6cd022',NULL,'singular noun','The horror of something, especially something that hurts people, is its very great unpleasantness.','...the horror of this most bloody of civil wars.',4,'/hɔrər/'),('flat','fe429c41643a56f74d5248374dd3ed79',NULL,'adjective','If trade or business is flat, it is slow and inactive, rather than busy and improving or increasing.','During the first eight months of this year, sales of big pickups were up 14% while car sales stayed flat.',3,'/flæt/'),('excitement','fe62a982f36f9619df0cd17677ac2502',NULL,'variable noun','You use excitement to refer to the state of being excited, or to something that excites you.','Everyone is in a state of great excitement.',4,'/ɪksaɪtmənt/'),('incense','fe699bc4fa47dccb8871f1de3544f6eb',NULL,'uncount noun','Incense is a substance that is burned for its sweet smell, often as part of a religious ceremony.','',3,'/ɪnsɛns/ /ɪnsɛns/'),('depression','fe94f39ef2da6141a9d99a0cb3acb9f2',NULL,'countable noun','A depression in a surface is an area which is lower than the parts surrounding it.','...an area pockmarked by rain-filled depressions.',4,'/dɪprɛʃən/'),('devoted','ff987fe48d7fe5901bd6d928cab1b85e',NULL,'adjective','If you are devoted to something, you care about it a lot and are very enthusiastic about it.','I have personally been devoted to this cause for many years.',4,'/dɪvoʊtɪd/'),('starve','fffb110918e3d4bf155b68251f634fd8',NULL,'transitive verb','If a person or thing is starved of something that they need, they are suffering because they are not getting enough of it.','The electricity industry is not the only one to have been starved of investment.',3,'/stɑrv/');
